<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 92 / Long campaign to mop up every poll-tax defaulter: Provisions
will be needed to cover many severe budget shortfalls
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY, BETHAN HUTTON and JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT says it is determined to close all legal loopholes open to
people who refuse to pay poll tax. But behind the ringing battle-cries from
ministers, a large number of local skirmishes is being fought by an army of
harassed council officers.
A survey of councils by the FT provides further evidence of their
difficulties and highlights the differing degrees of success among councils
in collecting the cash. Haringey: there are about 160,000 names on the
poll-tax register, and of those about 70,000 have not paid this year or are
seriously behind in their payments. A further 30,000 are in arrears. The
Labour-led council has collected Pounds 12m of the Pounds 49m due this year,
and expects to be Pounds 15m short at the end of the financial year. Last
year a shortfall of Pounds 15m meant that Pounds 61.85 had to be added to
the local poll tax. The council is block-booking courts to pursue
non-payers, although only one has been jailed so far.
Lambeth: an officer said the Labour-led authority's finances were in such a
mess because of internal difficulties and snags with computer systems that
it was unable to say how many people had not paid and how much was still
owed.
Kensington: the council could not give figures for the number of defaulters
because the population of the borough has a 50 per cent turnover rate each
year, and many people on the register are no longer liable for the charge.
Nevertheless, the borough had a high collection rate last year.
Westminster: the Conservative-led council has one of the lowest poll tax
levels in the country, at Pounds 36. Yet it also has 25,000 people on the
register who have not paid anything this year. That is almost 17 per cent of
the total number registered, though some may have moved. About 88 per cent
of the total due this year has been collected. The council did not
incorporate any allowances for non-payment into this year's charge and does
not foresee the need to do so when the charge level is set in March.
Southwark: the Labour-led authority has so far collected 58 per cent of the
Pounds 43m it is due to raise this year. Of the 175,000 people registered
110,000 are in arrears. Last year allowance was made for 20 per cent
non-payment, adding Pounds 64 to the charge. 'This year the collection rate
is about the same, and getting harder,' the council said.
Camden: the council has already taken all complete non-payers registered
through the court process, and has secured 58,245 orders, representing 44
per cent of its 131,917 total of people liable to pay poll tax. So far this
year 65 per cent of the Pounds 58m target has been collected. It is likely
that a surcharge of Pounds 60 to Pounds 70 will be added to next year's bill
to cover non-payment. The council added that the surcharge also covered
business rate defaulters. 'There has been a bigger shortfall of business
rates than we expected,' it said. 'It is an index of the recession and the
way businesses have been hit.'
Liverpool: poll tax difficulties have been made particularly acute for the
Labour-led city council because of computer difficulties and a long
industrial dispute. The Labour-led council faces a total of Pounds 45.6m (66
per cent) in uncollected poll tax bills this year and is having to build in
a Pounds 11.3m non-payment provision into its budget target.
Warrington: of 135,000 people liable for the charge, 12,699 have not paid
anything this year and the council has made a 5 per cent provision in its
budget for non-payment. Officials are reasonably confident of achieving 95
per cent collection this year. The poll tax is still likely to increase by
about Pounds 15, however.
Chesterfield: about 6,000 people (8 per cent) have paid nothing this year.
The local authority has made a 5 per cent budgetary provision for
non-payment. Next year the Pounds 263 poll tax is likely to be increased by
5 per cent to 6 per cent to cover non-payment.
Bristol: the city's poll tax of Pounds 369 is among the highest in the
country, and the Labour-led council does not hide the difficulties in
collection. 'The population has proved to be highly mobile . . . a
considerable number have simply disappeared off the face of the earth,' the
council said. Almost 100,000 people have been issued with summonses over the
past two years for non-payment or near non-payment. The figure may rise by
50,000 by the end of the current financial year. The total of 150,000
compares with 596,000 who are registered for poll tax. The council faces
Pounds 25m in accumulated arrears over the two-year period.
Newcastle upon Tyne: the city council says 14,400 of its 220,000 people
registered for poll tax have paid nothing. It has made a 5 per cent
provision for non-payment.
Manchester: 78 per cent of the council's expected figure for this year has
been collected so far. Next year's poll tax will not be increased to cover
the 1991-92 shortfall because the council can borrow for up to two years to
cover this. It will, however, have to be increased to cover the amount
written off from the 1990-91 non-collection - about 11 per cent to 12 per
cent of the total. That will add about 5 per cent to next year's bills.
'There seems to be a general feeling abroad that the poll tax has been
abolished and they don't have to pay, which isn't true, of course,' the
council said. 'We will be going for the money to the death - and beyond. I
can see us still collecting poll tax money in 1995.'
Birmingham: an assistant treasurer responsible for collecting poll tax said:
'The new figure for the poll tax is going to be political dynamite.'
</TEXT>
