<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 92 / Finance &amp; The Family: Quicker tax refunds agreed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UP TO 8m people will be able to receive repayment of tax on bank and
building society interest and on share dividends more quickly under new
measures announced by the Inland Revenue this week.
Non-taxpayers and those eligible for partial tax relief against bank and
building society interest income can now claim repayments worth more than
Pounds 50 immediately rather than having to wait until the end of the tax
year.
Those eligible for tax relief against income from share dividends -
including an estimated 2.5m married women who are independently registered
for tax - can also claim back payments on dividends without waiting until
after April 5 1992.
About 15m non-taxpayers have been entitled to register with their banks and
building societies to receive interest gross since composite rate tax was
abolished last April.
However, a large number of those who are eligible have not done so. Only
12.5m accounts, representing an even smaller number of people, have actually
registered for this facility.
The remainder can now apply for repayment directly under the new
arrangements. But the Revenue stresses that it would be simpler for those
who pay no tax to apply directly to their bank or building society to pay
interest gross.
The Revenue has now opened 24 repayment centres ahead of schedule, and will
be able to process any claims for relief above Pounds 50 immediately. Those
with reimbursements below this level must wait for the end of the tax year.
Inland Revenue leaflet IR 112 'How to claim a repayment of income tax'
explains the procedure for repayment of tax on share dividends; and leaflet
IR 111 'How to claim a repayment of tax on bank and building society
interest' explain the procedures required for repayment.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
