<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 92 / Finance &amp; The Family: CGT and assets
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TABLE above shows capital gains tax allowances for assets sold in
December. Multiply the original cost of the assets by the figure shown for
the month in which you sold them. If you subtract the result from the
proceeds of your sale, the difference will be your capital gain for tax
purposes.
Suppose, that you bought shares for Pounds 5,000 in July 1985 and sold them
in December 1991 for Pounds 12,000. Multiplying the original cost by the
July 1985 figure of 1.425 gives a total of Pounds 7,125.
Subtracting that from the proceeds of Pounds 12,000 gives a gain for tax
purposes of Pounds 4,875 - below the annual Pounds 5,500 CGT allowance. If
you realised no other gains during the year, the profit should be tax-free.
If you are selling shares bought before April 6, 1982, use the March 1982
figure.
