<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 92 / Money Markets: UK rates close level
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON LONDON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UK money rates were steady yesterday as sterling remained firm within the
European monetary system and the drain of tax payments from the market
decreased, writes Simon London.
The Bank of England forecast a shortage of Pounds 950m funds early in the
day. The main component contributing to the shortage was Pounds 735m in
maturing treasury bills and repurchase arrangements from earlier days.
Exchequer transactions, mostly comprising tax payments, drained Pounds 225m
from the market, a lower level than seen earlier in the week.
The Bank was able to inject a chunky Pounds 724m in early operations,
puchasing outright Pounds 139m band 1 bills and opening a new date for
repurchase funds. It bought Pounds 585m paper for resale to the market on
February 12 and 13 at 10 7/16 per cent.
This was sufficient to remove any pressure for higher overnight rates, which
fell back from 11 per cent on Thursday to 10 - 9 1/2 per cent by mid
morning.
In the afternoon session, just Pounds 10m band 1 bills were purchase before
late assistance of Pounds 185 mopped up the remaining shortage of funds.
The overnight money rate closed at 11 - 10 3/4 per cent; one-month interbank
funds closed unchanged at 10 3/4 -  5/8 per cent; three-month interbank
funds at 10 -  9/16 per cent.
In Frankfurt money market rates edged higher as operators anticipated a
squeeze in liquidity conditions next week as pension fund payments drain
funds from the market.
Anticipating this, the Bundesbank yesterday injected 'section 17' funds into
the market, transfering deposits held for the public sector into the
commercial market.
Call money was mostly traded at 9.45/55 per cent, from the 9.40/50 per cent
level which has prevailed all week.
The Bank of Japan kept liquidity conditions tight in Tokyo, despite another
heavy fall by Japanese equity prices. The Nikkei stock market index fell by
500 points, matching the scale of declines which led to a fractional easing
on money market conditions by the authorities earlier in the week.
Faced with an estimated Y290bn liquidity shortage, later revised down to
Y130bn, the Bank of Japan injected only Y100bn funds. As institutions
scrambled for funding, call money interest rates were squeezed up  1/8 of a
point to 5 per cent.
</TEXT>
