<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / International Company News: AT&amp;T falls 21% in fourth quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AMERICAN Telephone and Telegraph, the largest US long-distance telephone
carrier, yesterday reported a 21 per cent fall in its fourth-quarter net
profits to Dollars 635m (Pounds 350m), or 48 cents a share, compared with
Dollars 809m, or 64 cents, a year ago.
However, that drop included a one-time action, knocking 14 cents a share off
earnings, to reduce the book value of AT&amp;T's investment in the Italian
holding group Compagnie Industriali Riunite. Without that, earnings per
share would have been 62 cents. Revenues were little changed at Dollars
11.94bn, against Dollars 11.88bn.
All the figures include NCR, the large US computer manufacturer which AT&amp;T
acquired last September to give critical mass to its own ailing computer
operations.
While the recession was blamed for lower product sales, long distance and
financial services operations improved. AT&amp;T's sales of products and systems
dropped 7 per cent to Dollars 4.4bn.
There was a particularly large drop - 19.4 per cent to Dollars 1.08bn - on
the computer side, which the company said reflected general industry
weakness.
However, NCR reported record orders for the quarter, showing customers were
enthusiastic about new models it had introduced during the year.
Revenues for AT&amp;T's phone service business rose 6 per cent to Dollars 5.3bn,
on calling volume up nearly 6.5 per cent.
For the full year, AT&amp;T's net income was Dollars 522m, or 40 cents a share,
after taking Dollars 4.2bn of restructuring and other charges.
</TEXT>
