<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / International Company News: Sara Lee and Quaker Oats cheer
markets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO large US consumer product groups, Sara Lee and Quaker Oats, have
reported sharply-improved profits for the final three months of 1991.
Profits rose by 13.6 per cent at Sara Lee, the large Chicago-based consumer
products company, during the second quarter of its 1991-92 financial year,
to Dollars 189.4m after tax. Earnings per share increased by a roughly
similar amount, up 13.2 per cent to 77 cents, while net sales for the
quarter were Dollars 36bn, 6.8 per cent higher.
First-half net profits show a more dramatic advance, up by two-thirds to
Dollars 452.8m, but this partly reflects a net pre-tax unusual gain of
Dollars 221.7m - comprising profit from the sale of the pharmaceuticals
business offset by some restructuring costs. The gain was taken in the
July-September quarter.
At Quaker Oats, the food and pet foods group also based in Chicago,
second-quarter after-tax profits totalled Dollars 44.7m, against only
Dollars 2.1m.
Comparisons are muddied because of a Dollars 30m provision for discontinued
operations last year, but pre-tax profit from continuing businesses still
rose from Dollars 57.5m to Dollars 78.3m.
The company was helped by strong volume growth, at home and abroad, and
lower commodity costs. First-half profits stand at Dollars 87.1m after tax.
At close of trade shares in Sara Lee fell Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 53 1/2 ,
and those of Quaker Oats, were down Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 69.
</TEXT>
