<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / International Company News: Centel sale under consideration
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CENTEL, a Chicago-based telephone service company, yesterday underscored the
wave of consolidation sweeping through the US telecommunications industry
when it announced it would be examining the possible sale of the group as
part of a review of strategic options. Wall Street analysts reckon the
business could be worth around Dollars 5bn.
Centel, which has been through a restructuring programme to shed non-core
businesses over the past two years, serves about 1.6m telephone lines in
seven states and has a large cellular telephone business, operating in 44
urban areas and more than 50 rural ones.
Mr John Frazee, the chairman, said it had retained investment banks Goldman
Sachs and Morgan Stanley to explore strategic options. But he added that
Centel had not had any discussions or inquiries from outside parties about
the sale of either all or parts of the business.
He explained that Centel wanted to remain in charge of its fate while the
industry was consolidating, rather than possibly ending up as a bid target.
Centel stock soared by 25 per cent on the New York Stock Exchange to close
up 9 1/8 at Dollars 46 1/8 . Wall Street analysts said the group was most
likely to be sold off in pieces and that any of the seven 'Baby Bell'
regional telephone companies might be interested in parts, together with
GTE, the largest local operator in the US.
The analysts reckoned its break-up value could be between Dollars 55 and
Dollars 60 a share, based on eight to 10 times the cash flow of its
telephone operations and Dollars 200 for each potential subscriber (or
'pop') to its cellular network. Recent cellular deals have been struck
around Dollars 200 per pop.
Centel already has experience of hostile investors. In 1988 it fought off an
attempt to gain boardroom seats launched by Mr Asher Edelman, a New York
investor, and Mr George Lindemann, chairman of cellular group Metro Mobile.
Metro Mobile was sold last year to Bell Atlantic, one of the Baby Bells, for
Dollars 2.5bn. Other recent telecommunications takeovers include last year's
Dollars 6bn purchase of Centel by GTE.
Centel's growth in telephone business has been running ahead of the industry
average and its cellular business has also been growing strongly. The
group's fourth quarter results showed income from continuing operations of
Dollars 25.7m, or 30 cents a share, up from Dollars 10m, or 11 cents a year
ago, helped by a 14 cent gain on the sale of a cellular interest.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
