FT  24 JAN 92 / International Company News: Tandem Computers falls into red
in first quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TANDEM Computers reported a net loss for its first fiscal quarter after
restructuring charges. The manufacturer of fault-tolerant computers said
that economic and competitive pressures had permanently changed the computer
industry, writes Louise Kehoe.
The company reported a net loss for the quarter of Dollars 94.6m, or 88
cents a share including a restructuring charge of Dollars 80.5m, or 74 cents
a share. In the corresponding quarter of fiscal 1991, Tandem earned Dollars
7m, or 7 cents a share.
Revenues for the quarter were Dollars 454.5m, 2 per cent above the Dollars
443.8m in the same period a year ago.
Tandem reduced spending and cut its workforce in the first quarter. However,
'revenues were lower than we anticipated and our actions were not enough to
offset historically weak first quarter revenue patterns', said Mr James
Treybig, Tandem president and chief executive. 'Now we are moving to
restructure the company to increase both productivity and profitability.'
Earlier this month, the company announced restructuring plans to be
implemented over the next nine months, including consolidation of offices
and facilities, write-offs of assets and job cuts.
The company said that the restructuring would reduce expenses by Dollars 40
to Dollars 50m in the current fiscal year, and Dollars 90 to Dollars 100m in
fiscal 1993.
