<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AMDAHL, the IBM-compatible mainframe computer company, has, as expected,
incurred a fourth-quarter net loss. The company had projected a loss, citing
increasing softness in the European market which accounts for about one
third of the company's sales, writes Louise Kehoe.
The loss totalled Dollars 12.7m, or 11 cents a share, on revenues of Dollars
389.9m. It included a tax credit of 6 cents a share for the previous year's
losses in certain foreign subsidiaries. In the 1990 fourth quarter, the
company had net income of Dollars 61.3m, or 55 cents a share, on revenues of
Dollars 644.4m .
The company said fourth-quarter earnings were also adversely affected by
pricing pressures and high start-up costs associated with the introduction
of new products. A manufacturing problem, now corrected, also made it
necessary to suspend sales of some disk drives for some time.
Net income for all 1991 was down sharply to Dollars 10.6m, or 10 cents a
share, from Dollars 184m, or Dollars 1.66, in 1990. Revenues totalled
Dollars 1.7bn, down from Dollars 2.2bn.
