<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Tied agents 'are overselling life policies'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LIFE ASSURANCE and pen-sions policies sold through tied and direct sales
agents are much more likely to be terminated early than those sold through
independent financial advisers, according to a study undertaken for the
Securities and Investments Board, the City's chief investment regulator.
The study will provide ammunition for the SIB, which is considering
regulations which would require companies to tell customers more about
policies before a sale was completed.
The research commissioned by the SIB shows that up to 45 per cent of life
assurance and pensions policies sold through tied and direct agents are
terminated within two years. In contrast, policies sold through independent
advisers have cancellation rates ranging from 22 per cent to 32 per cent.
Sir David Walker, SIB chairman, has said high termination rates in early
years suggest consumers are being sold products which are unsuitable for
them. The SIB is considering new regulations which would require life
companies to disclose the size of refunds if policies were cancelled before
maturity.
Cancellation in the early years of a contract can cost the customer up to
100 per cent of all premiums paid because they are typically diverted at the
start of a policy to pay sales agents' commission and other administrative
fees.
The study found that between 23 per cent and 37 per cent of policies were
cancelled within two years, regardless of how the policy was sold. It said
early termination typically indicated 'overselling' or unsuitability. It may
also reflect high unemployment, recession, falling house prices or other
factors outside the control of sales agents or policyholders.
The study, which examined terminations in 1990, was completed in December
and surveyed the results of 61 UK life companies. It found that in all main
categories of product, independent advisers had a lower termination rate on
policies they sold than the industry average.
Unit-linked life assurance policies, for example, had an average 37.1 per
cent termination rate within two years. However, 39.2 per cent of policies
sold by direct sales agents and 40.1 per cent of those sold by tied agents
were terminated compared with 30.3 per cent of those sold by independents.
Non-linked life policies had an average termination rate of 23 per cent, but
24.7 per cent and 24.8 per cent of those sold respectively by direct and
tied sales agents were cancelled, compared with 22.1 per cent of those sold
by independent advisers.
The UK life assurance industry has moved to sign up banks and building
societies to act as exclusive sales outlets.
Editorial comment and Observer, Page 14
Across EC borders, Page 2
Sun Alliance job losses, Page 6
