<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / France set to tax dumping in attack on waste
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS and JOHN THORNHILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FRANCE yesterday launched an ambitious campaign against household and
industrial waste.
The scheme, drafted by Mr Brice Lalonde, environment minister, signals the
Socialist administration's sensitivity to the Green party's growing
popularity ahead of important regional elections in March.
The proposals, if implemented, would cost the public and private sectors an
estimated FFr15bn (Pounds 1.53bn) over 10 years. The government says they
would give France one of the world's most advanced systems for controlling
waste.
They are similar to last autumn's German plan centred on an annual levy for
collection of household refuse. The French proposals, which drew a hostile
response from international packaging companies yesterday, would impose a
FFr20 per tonne tax on the dumping of household and non-toxic industrial
refuse.
The tax is expected to raise FFr350m to FFr500m per year, enabling the
government's environment and energy agency to open 160 waste treatment
plants over the next decade. France's 6,700 public tips would be closed.
Producers of packaged goods would have to pay a levy of three centimes a
package. The project, adopted by the cabinet for presentation to parliament,
would oblige producers or importers of consumer goods to take back
packaging, or pay for a contractor to do so, from the start of next year.
The Industrial Council for Packaging and the Environment (Incpen), which
represents more than 60 international packaging groups, expressed strong
misgivings.
It said it was disappointed that many of the ideas for a more flexible
approach sketched out in a report on packaging waste by Mr Antoine Riboud,
chairman of the BSN food group, appeared to have been abandoned.
'If the French go the German route it would be disastrous,' Incpen said
yesterday. It has already lodged an official complaint with the European
Commission arguing that the German recycling system threatened the free flow
of trade across borders.
Other industry groups, such as the European Recovery and Recycling
Association, which represents consumer products companies and retailers,
have argued that recycling schemes should be commercially driven rather than
imposed.
The tax is designed to encourage industry and individuals to reduce the 70m
tonnes of waste they produce each year.
Yesterday's proposals include far-reaching plans for dealing with toxic
waste. These would require French companies to reach an agreement with the
environment agency under which they would treat their own toxic waste or
have it dealt with by specialists.
Green Germany, Page 2
</TEXT>
