<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / The Lex Column: EC insurance
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Two quite different events yesterday suggest that concentration in European
insurance is speeding up. The first was a meeting in Stockholm between four
leading Scandinavian insurers, which could lead to a new alliance grouped
round Sweden's Skandia. The other was a proposal by Italy's La Fondiaria to
reorganise three of its quoted subsidiaries into bigger units.
The latter can be seen as a purely domestic affair, inspired by the need to
tidy up La Fondiaria's sprawling corporate structure. But the move, which
involves putting three previously separate motor insurance activities under
one roof, has also been prompted by expectations that motor tariffs will be
freed from government restrictions at the end of this year. Speculation to
this effect has led to a 12 per cent jump in Italian insurance company
shares since Christmas.
While this may seem a national matter, it is worth remembering that the
Italians are only acting on motor tariffs because of an EC instruction.
Brussels legislation often seems divorced from commercial reality, but in
the insurance field it has already had a powerful political and
psychological impact. The same will no doubt be true of the key Third
Non-Life Directive, which provides for home country control and which almost
unnoticed was given the political go-ahead by the 12 last month. The single
market apart, the main factor driving mergers is the urgent need to address
the poor profitability of companies' core activities.
</TEXT>
