<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / The Lex Column: Hong Kong
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
There is something unnerving about a market which rises as fast as Hong Kong
has this year. A gain of nearly 8 per cent by yesterday suggests it is time
for a correction, especially since the inspiration for the final spurt was
classic froth - a false report that the Chinese government was dropping
criminal charges against former leader Zhao Ziyang.
Yet on a slightly longer perspective the heights reached by the Hang Seng
are not so giddy. Relative to Wall Street, it has only just made up its loss
following the Tiananmen Square massacre of 1989. It has still underperformed
the S&amp;P Composite by over 15 per cent since the October 1987 crash. Since
the market multiple of around 12 is not particularly expensive and the
territory is bound to benefit from the recent trade accord between the US
and China, there are solid grounds for presuming further upward movement.
Progress is unlikely to be linear, however, and the pace is being forced at
present because Hong Kong's link with the US dollar is holding money market
rates well below the 11 per cent inflation rate. This advantage should
unwind once US rates start rising again. The local prime rate has lagged the
money market as interest rates have fallen. Official worries about inflation
mean it is unlikely to do so as they come back up. By then a rising currency
could make local products less competitive just as export markets in Germany
and Japan are turning down. The resulting squeeze would leave equities
facing much less settled times.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
