<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / The Lex Column: Tiny's hand is frozen
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
FT-SE Index: 2,525.3 (+3.3)
Lonrho's full year figures are so startlingly bad as to raise the question
of whether some kind of denouement is finally at hand. In his recent choice
of chairman, Mr Rowland demonstrated that he could not provide a successor.
It now appears that he cannot provide adequate profits and dividends either.
The cut in the final payment may have been half expected, but not the 40 per
cent slump in second half profits and the passing of this year's first
interim. At last night's unofficial close of 120p, Lonrho has a market value
of under Pounds 800m and is heading out of the FT-SE. If the institutions
want change, they had better get on with it.
As always with Lonrho, the snag lies in assessing what Mr Rowland would
leave behind him. Its assets - the mines, the hotels, the newspapers and so
forth - seem solid enough. But so does the net debt of Pounds 1.1bn.
Granted, the figure is unchanged since the interim statement, while net
interest is apparently twice covered. But this makes the action on dividends
the more puzzling, particularly since there has been no obvious pressure
from the banks. A held annual total would have been only 90 per cent
covered, but Lonrho paid an 83 per cent covered dividend in 1982.
Without knowing what Lonrho is so worried about, valuation of the shares is
impossible. The market's working assumption is of 10p in total dividends
this year against 16p last, making for an 11 per cent yield at 120p. But
until the annual report is published, there is no telling what fresh horrors
are to come. Lonrho shareholders cannot say they were not warned. The
trouble is that they were not warned by Lonrho.
</TEXT>
