<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Deal near on BR break-up: Ministers support proposals to
keep InterCity network intact
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRIVATE regional rail compa-nies would run prestige national services on a
largely intact InterCity network under a plan emerging as a front-runner in
the cabinet committee considering British Rail's privatisation.
Ministers are nearing a compromise agreement on BR privatisation which could
pave the way for publication soon of a white paper setting out the
government's plans.
The Department of Transport hopes the deal will reconcile Mr John Major's
preference for reviving pre-war regional rail companies with the
determination of Mr Malcolm Rifkind, the transport secretary, who wants to
keep the privatised InterCity network as a viable entity.
Cabinet ministers have embarked on an intensive series of meetings on BR's
future in an attempt to resolve the row which has already delayed the white
paper at least once.
No final decisions have been taken on how the sell-off will be implemented,
but Mr Rifkind has said that a white paper would be published ahead of the
general election. There were suggestions at Westminster last night that it
might be released within two weeks, although a date later in February
appeared more likely.
The government originally hoped for publication late last year. With BR
privatisation set to be a central part of the Conservative party's election
manifesto, Mr Major is anxious to avoid unnecessary delays.
Ministers have agreed that BR's monopoly has to be broken and that private
operators must be given open access to tracks. They are also agreed that an
independent regulatory organisation would be required to resolve disputes
if, say, InterCity refused to permit access to its rail network.
Under the compromise now being worked on, companies for each region would
operate under a franchise system and would receive public subsidy. They
might be allowed to lay new tracks or use InterCity lines for running
services from provincial areas to London.
The freight network, which like InterCity is usually profitable, would
remain as one company and buy the use of track from InterCity and the
regional companies. Network SouthEast might remain in the public sector or
parts could be transfered to the regional operators.
Mr Major wants to revive the pre-war networks of regional companies - the
so-called 'golden age' scenario - but would have to accept InterCity
remaining in one piece if the compromise proposals were agreed.
Mr Rifkind wants to see an expanding rail network but fears that any
break-up of InterCity would lead to the abolition of many unprofitable
services.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
