<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Recruiters target ex-Soviet missile scientists
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRYSTIA FREELAND
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DNEPROPETROVSK, UKRAINE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FOREIGN headhunters are recruiting specialists from Dnepropetrovsk, the
missile-building capital of the former Soviet Union, to work in the Middle
East and elsewhere. Local businessmen say rocket scientists are among those
seeking to work abroad.
The recruitment drive at the centre where all Soviet intercontinental
ballistic missiles, including the SS18 and SS24, are built and designed
raises the spectre of Soviet arms technology proliferating to countries such
as Iraq, Iran and Libya.
Yesterday Mr Yuli Vorontsov, the Russian ambassador to the UN, denied
reports in an Arabic magazine that Iran had already purchased three nuclear
weapons, possibly from Kazakhstan, for between Dollars 130m (Pounds 71m) and
Dollars 150m.
The magazine, Al-Watan Al-Arabi, also claimed that Iran had hired more than
50 Soviet nuclear experts at salaries of Dollars 5,000 a month.
Proliferation of Soviet arms is a danger to which western leaders are
acutely sensitive. Yesterday on German radio Mr Hans-Dietrich Genscher,
Germany's foreign minister, warned that unemployed Soviet military
specialists are 'wandering technological mercenaries . . . easy prey for
recruiters for irresponsible potentates' who have the dangerous ambition of
building weapons of mass destruction'.
Mr Genscher proposed western states create funds to help prevent such a
brain drain. At the same time, officials accompanying Mr Roland Dumas, the
French foreign minister, on a visit to the former Soviet Union, said Russian
authorities might be willing to take legal action to prevent military
specialists from peddling their skills abroad.
But in Dnepropetrovsk fledgling entrepreneurs think military knowhow could
be one of their depressed region's most promising exports.
'If the Libyan government asked me to find rocket scientists I would be
happy help,' says Mr Viacheslav Kostiukovych, assistant director of Sistema
Reserve, an American-Ukrainian joint venture in the city which is primarily
involved in publishing.
Mr Kostiukovych has no doubt that if the price was right, Dnepropetrovsk's
military specialists would be willing and able to work abroad - he believes
some are already employed in the Middle East.
Sistema Reserve has an entree into the business: this spring it was asked by
the International Employment Agency, based in Liechtenstein, to recruit
specialists to work abroad, with special reference to the Middle East.
IEA emphasised that 'there is no limit to the amount of candidates that you
can recruit' and offered annual starting salaries of Dollars 30,000, (Pounds
16,600), a complete benefit package, pre-paid air fares and assistance in
obtaining visas.
Dnepropetrovsk is the home of Iuzhny Mashinostroitelny Zavod (Iuzhmash), the
largest integrated missile production facility in the world.
According to Mr Leonid Kuchma, the director of Iuzhmash, some 3,000 of the
50,000 people employed by the complex are specialists with knowledge of
sensitive rocket technology.
As the enterprise has shifted from 85 per cent military production five
years ago to a current 30 per cent, those specialists are now making
umbrellas, sausage-making machines and rose petal dryers instead of
missiles.
Mr Kuchma brushes aside fears of a brain drain to the Middle East butMr Iuri
Alexeyev, chief engineer is not so sure.
Ukrainian military, Page 2
</TEXT>
