<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Observer: Adios Granada
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The house of Warburg is not accustomed to being sacked. As the UK's most
successful investment bank, it can afford to be fastidious about the clients
it deigns to serve.
What an affront, therefore, when one of Warburg's less successful customers
dares to intimate that it might obtain better financial advice elsewhere.
Nevertheless, the defector, Gerry Robinson, new chief executive of
television and leisure group Granada, is clearly not in awe of Warburg's
reputation, even though partly indebted to the bank for his job. For
Warburg's part, having been dumped as Granada's financial adviser in favour
of Lazard Brothers, it has haughtily resigned from its separate role as
Granda's joint broker.
So why does the group want a new adviser? The official explanation is that
Robinson worked closely with Lazard when he headed Compass, a fast-growing
service company. But Granada was never happy about the high-handed way the
City demanded the sacrifice of the group's chief executive in return for
agreeing to a vital rights issue.
At the time, some Granada employees felt that Warburg had crossed the fuzzy
boundary between giving advice and interfering in the company's affairs. But
the money came rolling in, and as one Warburg wag said: 'It's the first time
anyone has been sacked for saving a company'.
Perhaps this sort of arrogance helps explain the decision.
</TEXT>
