<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / UK News (Employment): Struggle against ignorance and a lack
of interest - Promoting non-academic studies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS and LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHAT is an NVQ? Or a BTEC? Most people in Britain have not the faintest
idea.
Such ignorance sums up the country's training weakness, which Mr John Major
made a robust attempt to combat yesterday.
Asked recently by Gallup pollsters: 'Have you heard of national vocational
qualifications?' 61 per cent replied 'no'. Of those, more than half said:
'No, and I'm not interested.' Among semi-skilled and unskilled workers -
those for whom vocational qualifications are primarily designed - the
proportion saying 'no' rose to three quarters, with 50 per cent of the
unskilled uninterested.
True, almost half of those questioned believed that better training would
improve their performance at work - a marked improvement on previous
surveys. Marrying belief to remedy, though, has defied British policymakers
for a generation.
Measured by initiatives, the government scores highly.
In 1986 it established the National Council for Vocational Qualifications
(NCVQ) to streamline the plethora of existing qualifications and to accredit
NVQs (as they were named) for all levels of the workforce.
The council expects to complete the task by next year, working closely with
the three main providers of vocational courses, the Business and Technician
Education Council, City and Guilds and the Royal Society of Arts.
Last May came the government's white paper on education and training,
presaging most of the items announced by Mr Major yesterday.
In particular, it heralded 'general national vocational qualifications'  -
intended as full-time, vocationally oriented alternatives to A-levels to be
taken in schools and colleges - and 'advanced' diplomas  - to be awarded to
those with three A-levels or the vocational equivalent and intended to
constitute the minimum higher-education entry standard.
According to Mr Major, vocational qualifications deserve parity of esteem
with their GCSE and A-level counterparts - and, once they have gained it,
will generate a training revolution in Britain.
His optimism is shared by Sir Bryan Nicholson, chairman of the Post Office,
who also chairs the council. Sir Bryan wants to see 1m people with NVQs by
1995 (a tenfold increase on the present level), and boasts that by the end
of this year the council will have the framework in place.
'Thereafter, it will be a sweeping-up exercise and painting the Forth
Bridge,' he says.
The 1m target is ambitious. It cannot be achieved solely through training
young people, under government-funded schemes such as Youth Training, but
will rely on schools and training in the workplace. Only a handful of
schools has been persuaded to offer NVQs, and only a small cadre of
companies accounts for most of today's 100,000 people with NVQs.
Boots the Chemist, Safeway, Rover Group, B&amp;Q and WH Smith are prominent
among them. Boots is one of the most enthusiastic, after extensive piloting.
Boardroom scepticism remains widespread, however. One personnel director of
a large group declared himself not particularly concerned to promote NVQs
because he saw them as akin to other government-led initiatives - destined
to die when the next bright idea was launched. He also thought a Labour
government might abolish them - which Labour has always denied.
Other companies are wary. Asda, one of the largest food retailers in the UK,
is reviewing its participation in the scheme and may abandon it in favour of
an internal accreditation system, blaming the cost and inflexibility.
NVQs also have a long march ahead if they are to 'academic' courses. The
council's emphasis on testing competence in the workplace, rather than
setting examinations to be assessed externally, has limitations.
The Business and Technician Education Council (BTEC) first diploma in
business and finance, which claims parity of esteem with GCSE, comprises
such competence tests as these: file 20 consecutive documents correctly;
retrieve 20 items from a filing system correctly; correctly answer 10
incoming and outgoing telephone calls; take three oral messages accurately -
hardly a highway to university.
According to Mr Sig Prais, of the National Institute for Economic and Social
Research, much recent reform is 'purely cosmetic'.
He says: 'We are still a long way from the Continental idea of skill
training - which involves taking an examination course at college,
externally assessed, combined with practical experience at work.'
The council's mission is 'to provide the world's most effective national
framework of vocational qualifications'. A more modest goal of adapting to
British conditions the best on offer in Germany, France and the Netherlands
might be more appropriate.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
