<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / UK News (Employment): Major defends vocational
qualifications
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PRIME MINISTER yesterday announced a new set of vocational
qualifications which will be available as an alternative to A-levels from
September.
Mr Major, speaking at a conference organised by the National Council for
Vocational Qualifications, said good vocational education was not inferior
to a good academic education.
He said that old-fashioned prejudices and snobberies could have no place in
the world of education and should have no place in society.
Mr Major said general national vocational qualifications (GNVQs) would be
available for schools and further education colleges to teach from this
autumn. The qualifications are based on the new system of vocational
qualifications but will be less job-specific than the national vocational
qualifications (NVQs).
He also said that from 1994, 'advanced diplomas' will be awarded to students
with three A-level passes or 'equivalent' vocational qualifications. GNVQs
and diplomas were outlined in the education and training for the
21st-century white paper.
The prime minister also endorsed the target for 1m people to have achieved
NVQs by 1995, a target set by the National Council for Vocational
Qualifications. At present, about 100,000 people hold such qualifications.
Sir Bryan Nicholson, chairman of the national council and chairman and chief
executive of the Post Office, called on Britain's top companies to become
the first 1,000 to take up the challenge. Last year the Confederation of
British Industry, with the support of the government, the Trades Union
Congress and several other bodies set voluntary targets for the proportion
of people gaining NVQs.
Mr Jack Straw, Labour education spokesman, said Mr Major's speech was
'pathetic' and offered nothing new. 'This confirms the government has run
out of ideas about how to improve sorely needed skills in education and
training,' he said.
</TEXT>
