<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / UK News (Employment): Qualifications record of ET is
attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE THAN half of all trainees on youth training and Employment Training
programmes leave without a qualification, according to previously
unpublished figures revealed yesterday by the Labour party.
Mr Tony Blair, the shadow employment secretary, said that the Department of
Employment figures showed that only a third of those on Employment Training
(ET) obtained a qualification, while 67 per cent of Youth Training (YT)
trainees did not even gain a credit towards a national vocational
qualification.
The Labour attack came the day after a meeting of more than half the 82
Training and Enterprise Councils (Tecs) agreed to protest to the government
over the 'substantial reduction' in funding for training programmes, and was
timed to coincide with the prime minister's speech on training yesterday
afternoon.
Mr Blair added that only a quarter of ET trainees ended up in full-time
employment, while more than 60 per cent of ET and 35 per cent of YT trainees
were unable to get a job within three months of completing their course.
'The figures show conclusively that the government has been failing our
young people,' he said.
Mr Henry McLeish, an opposition employment spokesman, said: 'These figures
show the yawning gap between the rhetoric of the Conservatives and the
realities facing young people in Conservative Britain.'
New measures to improve relations between providers of Youth Training and
Tecs have persuaded the British Printing Industries Federation to reverse a
decision to stop being a managing agent for Youth Training.
The measures, drawn up by the Department of Employment, are due to be
announced next week. They will simplify the task cited by several large
companies of negotiating individually with the 82 Tecs and the 22 Local
Enterprise Companies, the Scottish equivalent to Tecs.
</TEXT>
