FT  24 JAN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Plea goes to EC over help for
region - Ravenscraig
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT has applied to the European Commission for leave to declare
an enterprise zone in north Lanarkshire to offset the impact of closure of
the Ravenscraig steelworks, Mr Ian Lang, Scottish secretary, said yesterday.
Mr Lang also told MPs he had written to Sir Bob Scholey, chairman of British
Steel about its proposals for Ravenscraig. His letter asks British Steel to
help deal with decontamination of the Ravenscraig site, partly by funding an
assessment to gauge which parts of it needed special treatment.
Mr Lang also asks British Steel to release evidence explaining why it had
opted for closure and to state how much extra funding will be provided to
British Steel (Industry) - a body set up to nurture new industries - to take
account of the additional job losses.
During a debate on Ravenscraig initiated by the Opposition, Mr Lang
challenged Labour to say how it would react to the situation. 'The party
opposite owes it to the House to tell us what they would do,' he said.
Earlier, Mr Donald Dewar, shadow Scottish secretary, had attacked government
inaction over Ravenscraig, which he said was typical of its 'hands-off,
do-nothing approach'.
While branding the government's package as 'incoherent and without shape',
he admitted there could be no promises of 'an overnight transformation.' He
did not consider nationalisation the answer.
Mr Dewar advocated keeping open 'as long as possible' the option of finding
a buyer while recognising the chances were slim. British Steel had probably
agreed to consider offers only because it doubted that there would be any.
An opposition motion condemning British Steel's repeated failure to invest
in its Scottish plants was defeated by 242 votes to 212.
</TEXT>
