<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Iveco Ford optimistic over recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IVECO FORD TRUCK, the UK's second-biggest truck maker, has joined market
leader Leyland DAF in forecasting a recovery in the depressed UK truck
market later this year.
Mr Alan Fox, managing director of the company, which is majority-owned by
Fiat of Italy's Iveco commercial vehicles division, suggested that sales
would rise by about 15 per cent to 37,000 units from last year's 32,184.
Statistics from the Society of Motor Manufacturers and Traders show the
present sales plunge to have been the sharpest since the Second World War.
The Iveco Ford forecast is slightly more pessimistic than that of Leyland
DAF, whose marketing and sales director, Mr David Gill, has suggested a
level of 38,000 to 42,000, depending largely on the outcome and timing of
the general election.
Backing for the recovery view was provided by SMMT statistics for December,
which showed a drop of only 12.37 per cent in sales of all commercial
vehicles, to 11,288, compared with the previous year's level.
Black Horse Financial Services, a Lloyds Abbey Life subsidiary that markets
financial services to Lloyds Bank customers, yesterday ordered 2,000 Rover
218SLD Turbo cars for its regional staff.
The order, worth Pounds 26.5m, is a boost for the diesel sector, one of the
few fast-growing sectors of the UK market for new cars.
</TEXT>
