<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Mortgage rescue scheme launched by Nationwide
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD and JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NATIONWIDE, the second-largest UK building society, launched the first stage
yesterday of a Pounds 150m mortgage rescue scheme to save 3,000 home owners
from losing their homes.
Mr Tim Melville-Ross, Nationwide's chief executive, said: 'We believe it
should be possible to find a solution for every borrower who is in the
'can't pay' category.'
It is the first of a series of rescue measures from lenders who promised the
government they would put up Pounds 1bn to halve the 80,000 mortgage
repossessions that otherwise appeared inevitable this year.
The first stage of Nationwide's scheme is an Pounds 8m agreement with three
housing associations: London &amp; Quadrant, Notting Hill Housing Trust and
Newlon Housing. The associations will buy 100 homes in the London area,
enabling their owners to stay as tenants.
Rents will be substantially lower than mortgage interest payments, at
between 3.5 per cent and 8 per cent a year of the value of the house. Mr
Melville-Ross said rents in London would be closer to the lower figure,
although they would be 15 per cent higher than normal housing association
rents.
Separate valuations will be carried out by the housing associations and
Nationwide, and borrowers will have their arrears wiped out only if they
stay with the scheme for three years. Each rescue operation will run for an
initial five-year period, which can be extended to 20 years.
About 12 other building societies are negotiating with nearly two dozen
housing associations and they are expected to announce similar schemes in
the next few months.
Nationwide is also negotiating a scheme with local authorities in which
borrowers and their families stay in their homes while the local authority
pays Nationwide a sum equivalent to the cost of bed-and-breakfast
accommodation.
Mr John Maples, economic secretary to the Treasury, welcomed the
initiatives, saying he expected them to be the first of many.
</TEXT>
