<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Government to move against
defaulters - Poll Tax non-payment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government is trying to bring a quick end to its embarrassment over poll
tax non-payment. The embarrassment has been caused by confusion in
magistrates' courts about whether computer records are admissible evidence.
Mr John Major's close interest in the issue is reinforcing pressure on Mr
Kenneth Baker, the home secretary, to produce proposals over the next day or
so to ensure computer evidence can be admitted.
Mr Michael Heseltine, the environment secretary, announced yesterday that
councils would be given more time to take enforcement action against poll
tax defaulters. 'There will be no amnesty for non-payers,' he said.
The two years at present available to councils will be raised to six years
under regulations to be made shortly.
Mr Heseltine's extension of the deadline for taking action blocks the
loophole that would otherwise have meant people who had not paid from 1990
could have escaped action.
The threat of poll tax enforcement descending into chaos has pushed the
issue high up the political agenda, to the government's discomfort, although
ministers make what they can of the involvement of opposition politicians in
non-payment campaigns.
The latest pressure comes from the decision on Wednesday by the Clerkenwell
stipendiary magistrate in London that Camden council could not rely on
computer records as evidence of non-payment in default actions against 12
Camden residents. That followed a similar decision by magistrates at Bury St
Edmunds in Suffolk three weeks ago, which prompted some other magistrates to
halt all their poll tax cases until the matter had been cleared up.
At Westminster, Labour has signalled willingness to co-operate in enabling
the regulations to be enforced urgently, although Mr Bryan Gould, shadow
environment secretary, said yesterday that 'Labour councils have been
warning for months of the dangers that computer-generated evidence might not
be valid, and the government should have moved months ago'.
There have been suggestions that if default cases heard so far are declared
invalid because of the loophole, the government might face claims for
wrongful imprisonment.
More than 1.8m summonses have been issued for non-payment in London since
the tax was introduced, according to the Association of London Authorities.
Letters, Page 15
</TEXT>
