<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Budget boost is urged to avert car factory closures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOTOR TRADERS were warned yesterday that 'there are now real concerns' over
possible car plant closures this year, with the possibility of new
Japanese-owned factories leading to overcapacity and threatening the
existence of UK manufacturers.
Sir Hal Miller, the Society of Motor Manufacturers and Traders' chief
executive and outgoing Tory MP for Bromsgrove, said that cuts in the tax
burden on the industry were essential if it was to recover from its present
decline. He was speaking as the society launched a campaign to raise
awareness of the motor industry among MPs and election candidates.
Measures it is suggesting in a pre-Budget submission to Mr Norman Lamont,
the chancellor, include abolition of the 10 per cent special car tax, higher
price thresholds for the taxation of company cars and concessions on value
added tax and national insurance contributions on the private use of company
cars.
Car and commercial vehicles sales have fallen by 30 per cent and 50 per cent
respectively in the past two years. Sir Hal warned that, without a Budget
stimulus, there was a risk of 'merely moving jobs from Dagenham to Derby'.
Car production at Toyota's Burnaston plant near Derby is due to start late
this year, as is production at Honda's plant near Swindon, Wiltshire. In the
past few days Nissan has announced plans to increase production from its
Sunderland plant by 50,000 to 270,000 cars next year.
The society is concerned about the severely depressed state of the UK
market, and about weakening demand in main European export markets that have
hitherto helped to keep UK car production relatively buoyant. That may lead
to an overcapacity crisis later this year and put established plants such as
Ford's Fiesta facility at Dagenham under pressure.
Unofficial calculations by the society suggest that the abolition of special
car tax might increase sales in a full year by 10 per cent.
Since the the organisation has already forecast a 10 per cent rise in sales
this year, to 1.75m units from 1.59m, abolition might therefore further
increase the size of the market to about 1.88m units. However, the society
is reviewing its forecast and may reduce it.
Nevertheless, Sir Hal struck a note of optimism when he claimed he had 'very
good reasons' for believing that Mr Lamont this year would act on at least
some of the industry's submissions.
At its meeting with the chancellor immediately after last year's Budget, the
society had warned that higher VAT, company car taxation and retention of
special car tax would significantly worsen the recession for the industry,
with 70,000 jobs likely to be lost in the two-year period up to the middle
of this year. Sir Hal said: 'It's turned out exactly the way we said it
would.'
</TEXT>
