FT  24 JAN 92 / Consultant offers hope for pits
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A CONFIDENTIAL report for the Department of Energy suggests that 30 pits
could produce coal at competitive prices. The the study, by John T. Boyd, a
US mining consultancy, has been passed to British Coal. Details of the study
appear in the latest issue of Coal UK, a Financial Times newsletter.
Boyd's conclusions mirror those of a study by the British Association of
Colliery Management, which has predicted that 30 mines could produce 49m
tonnes a year at competitive prices.
British Coal would still have to shut nearly half its pits, and the present
rate of closures and redundancies is likely to continue, according to Mr
Gerard McCloskey, consulting editor of Coal UK.
The newsletter says Hatfield, Bentley and Markham Main in the Yorkshire area
will be the next three closures among 55 working pits employing about 55,000
miners. Boyd differs from NM Rothschild, the merchant bank, which has
reported to the government that fewer than 10 pits are viable.
