<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / EC offers to spend more to aid mining areas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Commission is prepared to spend more to help British
coal-mining areas facing pit closures to create alternative jobs. In return,
the commission says the UK government must settle the row with Brussels over
how it accounts for such money.
The offer is likely to bring pressure on the government in the wake of the
job losses in the Yorkshire area announced this week, and claims that it is
not using the means available to safeguard people's livelihoods in those and
other threatened coal areas.
Mr Bruce Millan, the EC commissioner for regional policy, said yesterday
that Brussels had already allocated more than Pounds 30m to coalfields in
the Yorkshire area under the Rechar programme to help declining coal
regions. He 'was prepared to examine the possibility of increasing this
allocation', but was 'still awaiting assurances from the UK government that
when community funds are approved for particular areas they actually reach
the areas concerned'.
The commission has refused to disburse Pounds 109m under the Rechar
programme, and has warned that about Pounds 880m in regional aid for Great
Britain in 1992-93 is also 'in jeopardy', until Britain guarantees that the
EC money is 'additional' to government and local government funding of
projects.
British Coal said yesterday it did not rule out reopening talks with
Caledonian Mining, the unsuccessful bidder in the competition for leasing
Monktonhall colliery near Edinburgh. That follows a report that Monktonhall
Mineworkers, a company formed by redundant staff, had yet to complete its
business plan and secure finance.
