   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A NEW YORK judge yesterday rejected a request from Lloyd's of London to halt
a recent Dollars 550m settlement of federal fraud and racketeering charges
against the Bank of Credit and Commerce International (BCCI), Alan Friedman
reports from New York.
The London-based insurance institution, with other BCCI creditors, had tried
this month to block the settlement on the grounds that it would not leave
BCCI sufficient funds to pay creditors' claims.
Lloyd's had filed its own lawsuit, under US racketeering statutes, alleging
that it suffered losses on coffee transactions due to fraudulent behaviour
by BCCI.
Judge John Keenan ruled yesterday that the plea accord was 'a precisely
written, scrupulously constructed and rigorously negotiated document.'
