<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / US tries to save Mideast peace talks in Moscow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Agencies
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE US is working to save an important Middle East peace conference in
Moscow next week from the threat of a boycott by Israel's main Arab
adversaries, agencies report.
The two-day conference, scheduled to take place next Tuesday, is due to
discuss Middle East regional issues such as arms control and economic
development. It is seen as a crucial support pillar to the main bilateral
peace talks between Israel and its Arab neighbours - Syria, Lebanon, Jordan
and Palestinians from the occupied territories.
But Syria and Lebanon have already said they will boycott the meeting and
the Palestinians have yet to respond to the invitation because they resent
being lumped together with Jordan in a joint delegation.
In a separate development, the US secretary of state, Mr James Baker, had
been scheduled to inform Israel yesterday of Washington's decision on its
request for Dollars 10bn (Pounds 5.5bn) in housing loan guarantees. But a US
spokesman said the meeting between Mr Baker and the Israeli ambassador, Mr
Zalman Shoval, would be held today and indicated the US might not be ready
to give Israel its decision at the meeting.
The US decision on loan guarantees could have crucial implications for the
peace process. Arab foreign ministers are scheduled to meet in the Moroccan
city of Marrakesh today to co-ordinate positions on the issue and a decision
on Palestinian participation was expected to follow soon after.
Meanwhile, Israel yesterday revoked an expulsion order against one of 12
Palestinians facing ejection from the occupied territories following a spate
of attacks on Jewish settlers. It was only the second time that the Israeli
authorities have reversed an expulsion order. The last time was in 1979.
</TEXT>
