<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Western nations rally to rescue their former foe: Why the
conference on aid to the former Soviet Union has been a useful first step
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER and QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Washington conference on co-ordinating emergency humanitarian aid to the
former Soviet Union proved more useful than its many critics first
suspected.
At the end of the two-day meeting yesterday, most leading participants said
the conference marked an important first step in mobilising international
public support for aid to the one-time superpower.
'A process has been started,' said Mr Hans-Dietrich Genscher, the German
foreign minister who has long argued for large-scale western aid to pre- and
post-communist Russia as a catalyst for reform.
The big question, of course, is how far this global effort will go; at what
point will the west, notably the US, be called upon to put up money to
support the risky and immensely costly macro-economic reform in the former
Soviet republics.
The Bush administration pre-empted this debate last month by calling for a
conference on humanitarian aid alone. Some 47 countries and five
international financial organisations, including the International Monetary
Fund and the World Bank, accepted the invitation.
The US demarche upset European sensibilities, but President Bush defused
criticism during generous opening remarks at the opening of the meeting in
which he tried to reassure allies that the US intends to pay its way in
future Soviet aid.
Mr Bush lavished praise on the European Community and Germany for their own
aid effort; he announced he was seeking Dollars 645m in fresh technical and
humanitarian aid from Congress; and he agreed to a follow-up conference in
Lisbon, sponsored by the European Community and to be attended by the
republics.
This week's focus among the working groups was short-term disaster relief:
how best to ship and distribute food and medicine to cities where the worst
shortages are located; and how to avoid the corruption and bureaucratic
snarl-ups which have plagued the relief effort.
The aid pledged so far will not be enough to feed the Soviet people, but the
conference participants felt enough food was in the pipeline to avoid
starvation this winter. Mr Douglas Hurd, British foreign secretary, observed
that the relief effort remains crucial 'at the margin' - unblocking
bottlenecks and seeking out the most vulnerable areas.
The US announcement that it is starting military airlifts on February 10
should be taken in the same spirit of solidarity. In volume terms, the
proposed 54 C-5 Galaxy transport flights are not impressive; the broader aim
is to show the Soviet and American people that the Cold War is over and the
west is prepared to help its old adversary.
This education of ordinary Americans is easily underestimated. Having been
brought up on a diet of anti-communism for more than 40 years, Americans
need to be persuaded of the wisdom of sending direct financial aid to the
former Soviet Union, particularly during a recession which has highlighted
the country's own domestic problems.
The military airlifts may be a headline-grabbing gimmick, but they also help
prepare the political case for financial aid which - in Mr Hurd's words -
lies just over the horizon. Indeed, British officials stressed this week
that humanitarian aid is merely a short-term remedy, not a long-term
solution.
In order to avoid a 'dependent culture' growing up in the Soviet republics,
the reformers must be pushed into another leap toward a free market - with
the clear prospect of international support, a British official said.
This coincides with the German view. During a long news conference at the
Watergate hotel, Mr Genscher mixed his lengthy description of the German
relief effort over the years with one newsworthy remark: that the issue of
financial aid to the former Soviet Union was certain to be discussed at the
Group of Seven industrialised nations meeting in Munich in July of this
year.
The G7 conference will be chaired by Germany; and unlike the previous
conferences held in Houston and London, this meeting will be discussing
large-scale aid not for a reformist communist Soviet leadership led by Mr
Gorbachev but 11 republics in the Commonwealth of Independent States.
European diplomats said this week they were leaning hard on the IMF to speed
up membership for Russia and other republics. This would allow them to
borrow to support a stabilisation fund for currencies and, perhaps, a
payments union to ease trading problems between the republics. The World
Bank stands ready to commit money, too, beyond the current technical aid.
This is the point where the tough decisions on financial aid will have to be
taken in Washington. For all the heady rhetoric about the 'global coalition'
for freedom heard at the State Department this week, the moment of reckoning
is approaching fast.
FORMER Soviet republics like Ukraine, which have yet to sign the
western-inspired memorandum of understanding on repaying the debts of the
former Soviet Union, could be refused membership of the International
Monetary Fund, writes Quentin Peel in Bonn.
Germany will press at the G7 meeting to block membership for those not
prepared to honour Soviet debts, not with the aim of excluding them, but
rather in the hope of forcing them into line.
Ukraine is by far the most important of the four which have so far refused
to accept responsibility. The others are Azerbaijan, Georgia and Uzbekistan.
Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania, which were forcibly incorporated into the
Soviet Union in 1940, have rejected responsibility for a share of the Soviet
debt apart from that related to projects in the Baltic states.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-12782</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CAXBAAEQFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920124
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Lobbyists fight shy of Strasbourg register
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Parliament is considering a code of conduct for the estimated
3,000 professional lobbyists who have established themselves in Brussels to
influence Community laws and decisions.
This move parallels a similar step by the European Commission, whose 1992
work programme, to be unveiled next month, also talks of the need for a
proper code of conduct between the Commission and pressure groups.
For all their mock horror at the growth in Euro-lobbying, most EC
legislators and officials are privately delighted that so many people now
consider them worth influencing. But as the stakes mount, so does industry
pressure, with, for instance, the tobacco lobby now pulling out all the
stops to head off a near-total ban on tobacco advertising.
Two days of public hearings this week gave professional lobbyists the
unusual chance to lobby in favour of themselves rather than their clients.
Most of them baulked at having to register as lobbyists, as they are
required to do in the US and Germany.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-12783</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CAXBAAEPFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920124
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Green Germany drags Brussels into environmental arena
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER, QUENTIN PEEL and JOHN HUNT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS, BONN, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
YESTERDAY'S French government proposals inject a potent factor into EC
policy-making on the environment.
The packaging industry and several national governments have been concerned
to prevent the European Commission from modelling its forthcoming directive
on recycling of packaging too closely on Germany's radical legislation
outlined last autumn.
The hostile reaction yesterday to the French proposals from Incpen, the
council representing more than 60 international packaging groups, indicates
the gulf between industry and governments which now appears to be opening
up.
Officials in Brussels see environmental legislation as possibly the most
difficult example of framing common rules to bridge the Community's
north-south gap.
Measures in this field must encompass both the concerns of the rich, 'green'
northern countries, such as Germany and Denmark, and those of poorer
southern countries seeking to catch up with northern living standards which
see much EC environmental law as an expensive obstacle.
Unless this circle is squared, achieving a common policy will be difficult.
Proliferating national laws on the environment could, Commission officials
fear, erect new barriers to competition and trade within the single market.
The German packaging law has already raised complaints that products from
elsewhere in the EC will face discrimination inside Germany, and that the
sheer volume of recycled packaging will overflow German borders to stifle
efforts by its neighbours to get recycling schemes under way.
Yet the latest versions of Brussels' long-delayed plans - still to be
approved by the Commission, much less passed into law by the 12 - are less
exacting than Germany's rigid standards. Officials say plans now aim to
ensure that, within 10 years, 90 per cent of all packaging is reused,
recycled or burnt for energy, and at least 60 per cent would have to be
reused or recycled.
Earlier drafts set targets of 60 per cent overall 'recovery' of the waste
and 40 per cent recycling, but over five years.
It also now seems unlikely that Brussels will press for an EC levy on
packaging to help fund recycling.
The drive for tough waste and recycling standards is one sign of the
environmental pressure emanating from Germany, which is well ahead of the
rest of Europe in this field. The west of the country alone produces an
annual 80m tonnes of industrial waste, and up to 40m tonnes of household
rubbish.
Britain, by contrast, is taking a totally different approach to Germany on
waste disposal, based on deregulation rather than new legal measures.
The Environmental Protection Act lays down that local authorities can no
longer run a waste disposal site and regulate it as well. The functions are
separated and the authorities have to set up companies that operate at arms
length to dispose of waste. In fact, many will be putting out the work to
the private sector.
A much more vigorous approach has been adopted by Bonn.
In the past year, Mr Klaus Topfer, the environment minister, has introduced
a series of initiatives to force German industry to recover and re-use or
re-process increasing proportions of waste.
By 1995, German industry will have to collect 80 per cent of all plastic
waste produced, and recycle 80 per cent of that. Similar targets have been
set for board and paper packages, and higher standards still for glass,
tin-plate and aluminium.
Last summer, Mr Topfer produced further plans for manufacturers to take back
used cars and household electronic appliances.
In the autumn, he proposed a new rubbish surcharge of up to an annual DM10
(Pounds 3.40) per head, with special charges of up to DM200 per tonne for
industrial waste.
In December, he introduced minimum quotas for re-usable bottles for drinks,
and for re-usable packaging to put them in.
At the heart of the recycling effort is the so-called 'green spot' system,
called Duales System Deutschland (DSD), set up by 440 companies to establish
the infrastructure needed to recover and re-use packaging waste.
Companies pay the DSD to have a green spot attached to their products,
showing that they can be returned and re-used. The money charged is supposed
to pay for the cost of running the scheme.
Ironically, the greatest outcry has come not from German industry, but from
foreign companies, fearing they will be disadvantaged on the German market
without green spot packaging.
Latest reports suggest that the scheme is not working as well as intended,
because of a lack of recycling facilities to receive the packaging.
More than 3,000 companies have signed up to put the spots on some 6bn
packages since the scheme came into effect last autumn. By the end of 1992,
the number is supposed to have increased tenfold.
</TEXT>
