<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Yarrow wins Pounds 400m navy order
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE, JAMES BUXTON and CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A CRUCIAL order for three new Royal Navy frigates worth almost Pounds 400m
went yesterday to Yarrow Shipbuilders of Glasgow after a fierce competition
with rival yards.
The order, announced in the Commons by Mr Tom King, defence secretary,
ensures work for the Clydeside yard well into the mid-1990s and leaves all
three other UK naval yards still searching for shipbuilding orders for that
period. About half the total value will go to Yarrow, a subsidiary of
Britain's General Electric Company (GEC).
Defence officials said it had been 'a clear win on cost grounds' against
bids from VSEL of Barrow-in-Furness, Swan Hunter of Tyneside and
Southampton-based Vosper Thornycroft.
The government, however, is widely seen as also having had strong political
reasons for wanting to place the work in Scotland, especially after the
announcement earlier this month of plans to close the Ravenscraig steel
complex in Lanarkshire with the loss of 1,200 jobs.
Workers at Yarrow reacted with delight and relief to the news that they had
won the order for all three frigates. 'It's excellent,' said one of the
shipbuilding workers. 'It means job security for the next three years,' said
another.
Local Labour politicians and trade unionists had raised the possibility of
the yard closing down if the order had gone elsewhere. That idea was
dismissed earlier this week by Sir Robert Easton, Yarrow's chairman.
Sir Robert said yesterday, however, that redundancies would still be needed
before work began on the new ships unless further orders were secured.
Yarrow, which has been in negotiation with Malaysia over an order for two
corvettes, shed 645 jobs late last year, reducing the workforce to 2,750.
The contract follows a recent Pounds 200m order for four chemical carriers
won by Kvaerner Govan, the Norwegian-owned merchant shipyard on the other
side of the Clyde.
It is also the second big defence order for GEC this week. The group leads
an international consortium which will provide electronic warfare equipment
potentially worth Pounds 1.5bn for the European Fighter Aircraft.
Yarrow, which lost the competition for the last batch of warships to Swan
Hunter, has now won nine of the 13 orders placed for Type 23 anti-submarine
frigates.
Officials said placing orders in batches had proved much less expensive than
spreading them between different yards. Work on the new ships is due to
begin late this year and continue for about four years.
At least one further batch is planned, but that order is expected to be
about two years away. Future Royal Navy orders are not expected to be
sufficient to sustain all four yards, which were privatised in 1985-86.
Swan Hunter, which currently employs 3,800 including 1,000 on short-term
contract, said it was 'naturally disappointed' that its 'extremely
competitive bid' had failed.
VSEL, which currently has no orders for surface warships, said it still
needed a share of the frigate programme to provide work following completion
of Trident nuclear-missile submarines.
Vosper Thornycroft said it would also keep trying for a share of frigate
orders.
The Ministry of Defence also announced yesterday it was buying the
ice-breaker Polar Circle, which it currently leases, from Rieber Shipping of
Norway to replace HMS Endurance in the South Atlantic. The price was not
disclosed.
</TEXT>
