<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Banker to succeed departing SIB chief
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS and PETER MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR DAVID WALKER, tipped as a possible candidate to become the next governor
of the Bank of England, yesterday announced a surprise decision to step down
as chairman of the Securities and Investments Board, the City's chief
investment regulator.
He will leave at the end of May, when his current four-year term ends.
Explaining his departure, Sir David, 52, who was asked to take on the post
in 1988 after other candidates turned the position down, said: 'I don't want
to retire a regulator.' He said he was looking for a new job in the private
sector, but did not yet have another position to go to.
His job is to be taken by Mr Andrew Large, a 49-year-old banker. A former
chairman of The Securities Association, one of the City's self-regulatory
organisations, Mr Large was the first Briton to be appointed to the main
board of a Swiss bank when with Swiss Bank Corporation in the mid-1980s.
Sir David was sent into the SIB at a time of widespread City concern about
the bureaucratic and costly system of regulation that had been set up by his
predecessor, Sir Kenneth Berrill.
A former executive director at the Bank of England, where he still sits as a
non-executive director, Sir David's forceful style and impatient manner have
at times antagonised the self-regulatory organisations which come under the
SIB's control. They have also enabled him to push through extensive changes
to the regulatory system set up under the 1986 Financial Services Act.
Sir David said he had warned of his intention to leave the SIB last
September, but had offered to stay for a further short period beyond the end
of his existing term if needed. The offer was not taken up by Mr Peter
Lilley, trade and industry secretary, and Mr Robin Leigh-Pemberton, current
governor of the Bank, who jointly appoint the SIB chairman.
The announcement of Sir David's departure comes as the SIB is close to
finalising its policy on the selling of retail investment products such as
life assurance and unit trusts - one of the most difficult and important
aspects of its work.
Policy decisions are expected to be taken before Sir David departs on
several important aspects, including how commissions are paid on life
assurance policies. But other aspects of retail regulation, such as the
future of Fimbra, the financially troubled watchdog for independent
financial advisers, will be left to Mr Large.
Observer, Page 14
Life policies 'oversold', Page 16
</TEXT>
