<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Survey of FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (35):
PostScript
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TIMES HAVE not been propserous for collective-fund investors. Even with the
recovery in world stock markets during 1991, ten out of the 15 unit trusts
sectors covered in our tables, and ten out of the 13 investment trust
sectors, have incurred a loss over the last two years.
Worst of all were those trusts investing in Japan, with the average unit
trust in the area losing 35 per cent over two years, and the average
investment trust more than 40 per cent.
Even over the longer five-year period, many trusts failed to beat the 64.6
per cent return on index-linked National Savings. Four investment trust
sectors managed to do so, but no unit trust sector achieved this feat.
The brightest sector has been UK income growth investment trusts, several of
which now stand at a premium to net assets. The elimination of the discount
has boosted the share-price performance of this sector. The individual
investment trust leader over five years is the tiny Capital Gearing trust.
Among unit trusts, the five-year champion is Newtown Income; the recent poor
performance of the Japanese stock market has meant that the previous star,
Schroder Japanese Smaller Companies, has slipped back.
The five-year performance records of collective funds ought to pick up in
November, when the 1987 stock market crash will start to drop out of the
statistics.
For the moment, it is really only over the 10-year span that the benefits of
collective fund investment can be seen. The average UK equity income trust,
for example, turned Pounds 1,000 into Pounds 5,033 between January 1982 and
January 1992, and the Key Income fund turned the same sum into Pounds 7,480.
The difficulty for potential investors is that past performance, while a
useful guide, sends out some contradictory signals. Capital Gearing has
turned Pounds 1,000 into Pounds 2,625 over five years, but over the last two
years it has turned Pounds 1,000 into Pounds 536. Which is the better
indicator of its future performance? Fidelity Japanese Special Situations is
seventh in its sector over five years, but 67th over two.
Nor do the performance figures settle the thorny question of whether unit or
investment trusts offer the better prospects to the small investor.
Investment trusts seem to have the performance edge, as measured by these
tables, but a good deal of this due to discounts narrowing. Such narrowing
cannot occur again. Indeed, the volume of investment trust new issues
creates a chance that the discount could widen once more. The relative
performance of unit trusts could look alot better in five years time.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
