<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Survey of FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (36):
Massive interest over five years - The Business Expansion Scheme / The
Budget is likely to see the end of buy-back schemes, which may seem too
generous a tax-break for the benefits they deliver, and are not a suitable
home for all your savings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STAND BY for a clearance sale by Business Expansion Scheme companies in the
run-up to the budget. Schemes that seek to assure a fixed return after five
years are expected to be abolished.
In many ways, it is surprising that the government allowed them to start in
the first place; yet such a move would also be a shame. For these schemes
have finally won support for the BES from the mainstream intermediaries and
accountants who control most of the UK's investment business. Previously, it
had seemed too speculative for small investors.
At first, the BES may not seem to have much to do with mainstream personal
finance. It was set up in 1981 as the Business Start-up Scheme, to stimulate
investment in high-risk small companies - and many early BSS companies
indeed lived up to the 'high-risk' label.
Since then, it has regularly been altered. In 1988, the scheme was opened to
investment in 'assured tenancy' rental accommodation, to help the private
rental sector. The housing side of the BES now predominates  - the maximum
size for a BES tenancy company is Pounds 5m, but for trading companies the
limit is only Pounds 750,000.
The broad outlines for private investors are as follows. You can invest up
to Pounds 40,000 in companies which qualify for investments under the BES.
You then submit a BES3 form (sent to you by the company) to the Inland
Revenue. The total value of your investment is then deducted from your total
taxable income. Thus, if you are a 40 per cent taxpayer, you will receive a
rebate of 40 per cent of the amount you invested. So you ultimately part
with only Pounds 24,000 to invest Pounds 40,000.
You may lose this relief if you do not hold on to your BES shares for at
least five years; otherwise, provided you can sell the shares, you should
make a substantial profit. However, making a clean exit from the company has
proved difficult for many of the trading companies which have now finished
their five years, and this, combined with the speculative nature of the
investment, has deterred investors.
The new concept of covenanted buy-back companies attempts to ensure an exit
route, and also a specific yield. BES sponsors go to providers of low-cost
rental housing - usually colleges or housing associations - and offer to buy
them some property. In return, the association or college must covenant to
buy back the property, for a fixed price, when the five-year BES term has
elapsed.
The fixed price will typically be around 35 per cent or 40 per cent higher
than the price paid initially. now. This provides the covenanting housing
providers with reasonably cheap finance, and they have the use of the
housing stock for five years. But they are 'taking a punt' on house price
inflation. If they cannot afford the covenanted price after five years, they
are legally obliged to borrow to meet it. This would have the unfortunate
effect of using substantial tax relief from the Treasury to force worthy
organisations into debt.
However, the odds are that the covenanting bodies will do well out of the
deals. The only risk for investors comes if they go out of business
altogether.
The exit route would then be much less secure, as, in most cases, there is
no third-party guarantor. These schemes are not entitled to describle
themselves as 'guaranteed', despite some early marketing claims.
However, one scheme launched in September - IM Assured Growth - had a
guarantee from the Bank of America. It was quickly oversubscribed. This type
of scheme seems likely to spread.
If you are a 40 per cent taxpayer, and have money to put away for five
years, these schemes may deserve attention. Interest rates after tax-relief
are massive. For example, Johnson Fry's Seventh Super Growth offers the
equivalent of 16.5 per cent annually, roughly double what you might hope to
get from a five-year guaranteed income bond.
The problem with the 'buy-back' schemes is that they seem far too generous a
tax-break for the actual benefits they deliver. The latest edition of the
Investor's Chronicle Beginners' Guide to Investment described the practice
as 'arbitraging the taxman'. Certainly, the schemes are far removed from the
original principle of encouraging investors to take risks.
However, Stephen Bantoft, BES analyst of the Allenbridge Group, points out
that they offer the security of a long-term owner, and should therefore do
more to encourage lasting housing provision for the needy. Schemes aiming to
sell to a private owner in five years might provide only a brief interlude
of private rental housing, and are of less help to the country's current
housing crisis.
The other main class of BES company is the 'predator'. These do not have the
secured exit route, but aim to profit to the full from the current depressed
residential property market. Thus they buy now, let the houses to private
tenants for five years, and then sell, hoping to make a profit.
There could be problems with exit routes. Otherwise, the strength of the
investment depends on your reading of the residential property market. The
central problem is that the BES is an inappropriate vehicle for housing
subsidies. If the upper limit for investments in trading companies were
raised, things might be different.
Several operators are looking at ways to extend the 'buy-back' principle to
trading companies. For example, the BES might be used to finance individual
supermarkets or petrol stations for larger chains, who would buy them after
five years. This would be an interesting development, returning the scheme
to its original intentions, but in a form which might allow average small
investors to benefit. It also effectively circumvents the Pounds 750,000
limit.
For the time being, tread carefully, but keep an eye open for opportunities.
The view of David Harris, of accountants Chantrey Vellacott, is typical:
'I'm fairly positive with regard to the so-called guaranteed schemes. If you
are prepared to accept that there's a limited risk, it's definitely
something you should consider as part of a broader portfolio. But it would
be lunacy to take everything out of the Halifax tomorrow and put it in a BES
residential scheme.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXXVI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
