<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Survey of FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance - Personal
Equity Plans (26): The tax-free route to a stake in your employer -
Single-company PEPs / Shares bought through a SAYE scheme can now be
transferred directly into a Pep
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THIS YEAR's newcomer in the Pep market is the single-company Pep.
Investors are already entitled to use Peps for holding shares in only one
company if they wish. Such vehicles have a limit of Pounds 6,000.
But these plans cannot provide diversification, and so make little
investment sense. They were likely to be of most use to executives and
employees who had built up shares in their own companies through option
schemes, allowing workers a tax-free way to hold the proceeds.
Single-company Peps - otherwise, SCPs or Copeps - were introduced in the
last budget to recognise this. Since the beginning of this month, investors
have been allowed to invest an additional Pounds 3,000 in a single-company,
on top of Pounds 6,000 in a mainstream Pep. Transfers of shares bought via
an approved SAYE scheme can be made directly to a Pep, saving the expense
and bother of selling them, and then buying them back into a Pep, as is
currently necessary.
A number of companies - including such blue-chip names as BP, ICI, Glaxo and
BAT Industries - sponsor their own Peps. Other companies are planning to
launch them. Much of the running in this market has been made by Bradford &amp;
Bingley, and CC&amp;P Trustees, which is now a division of Bacon &amp; Woodrow. The
FT-SE 100 companies and their intentions are listed below
These Peps will be particularly attractive to company employees. In some
ways, they can be set apart from the main bulk of portfolio management and
financial planning. However, institutional fund managers are also cashing
in. In practice, you can buy a tax-free Pounds 3,000 stake in virtually any
quoted company, even if you do not work for them.
Many managers are offering a free choice of any quoted company, or in some
cases a choice of any FTSE stock. If the company you wish to invest in does
not have its own Pep, then this is the route to take.
Choosing a Pep manager in these circumstances is simple. Go for the
cheapest.
The only other factor is to check the company's financial strength. The
collapse of Diameter Stockbrokers last year led to lengthy hassle for its
Pep-holders, as ownership was often difficult to establish. The bigger
institutional fund managers might, therefore, make sense.
These Peps still have the significant advantage over other plans that most
do not suffer from the heavy dealing costs involved in active management. It
does not cost much to buy a block of shares and then hold on to it. If you
choose a large, secure company, with every prospect of continued high
dividends, then a Pounds 3,000 Pep should be a sound investment, provided
you hold it for the long term.
Some managers, such as Reyker Securities and John Siddall &amp; Son, will offer
discounts by combining the Pounds 3,000 single-company Pep with a Pounds
6,000 standard Pep.
It is open to question whether the big fund managers offer the best value
for money. For example, NatWest Bank charges an initial fee of Pounds 30,
with a half-yearly management charge of 0.25 per cent plus VAT. There is no
start-up fee for existing NatWest planholders. It offers a range of 60
companies for investment.
This is a good deal. But if you invest in ICI, one of the companies offered
by NatWest, through its own sponsored Pep, managed by Bradford &amp; Bingley, it
should work out cheaper. There is no initial charge, and management charges
are Pounds 5 plus VAT per half year, which works out, unless the price of
the shares drops considerably, as being rather cheaper than NatWest's
management charge. However, there is a fee of Pounds 5 plus VAT when the Pep
is closed.
If you want to invest in ICI in any case - and it is part of many portfolios
 -then ICI's sponsored Pep seems to be a very sensible way to do it.
But in general, although these plans provide some interesting opportunities
for general investors, they are of most use to those who already have a
large portfolio, and want to protect some of it from tax. Unless you are in
that bracket, unit and investment trust Peps, with possibly some blue-chip
equities on top, should take priority over a single-company Pep.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXVI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-12807</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CAXBAAD1FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920124
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Survey of FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance - Personal
Equity Plans (25): Cheap if you have the time - Self-select PEPs / There
should be no management fees. Charges will be weighted on the dealing side -
to the disadvantage of those who deal often
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SELF-SELECT Peps are most likely to appeal to investors who like to play the
stock market themselves. As the name suggests, the investor chooses a
portfolio of shares, in contrast to the more common managed Peps which are
run by fund managers.
'You must know what you are doing,' said Roz Barder, of Chase de Vere
Investments, which publishes *Pepguide.
Those who do not have the time or the inclination to manage their own
portfolio would therefore be well advised to steer clear of self-select
Peps.
The advantage of self-select Peps is that they are often cheaper than those
that are managed; and, since you choose what and when to buy, you are not at
the mercy of fund managers' decisions. Nevertheless, you still have to go to
a plan manager to get a self-select Pep, because only they are authorised to
run plans.
There is a basic difference in the charging structures of self-select and
managed Peps. The latter usually carry an initial charge of anything between
1 and 6 per cent, and an annual management charge of about 1 to 1 1/2 per
cent, with VAT on top. There will often be charges each time that you deal.
By contrast, there should be no management fees to pay on a self-select Pep
 -if there are, look elsewhere. Instead, the charges will be weighted on the
dealing side. This means that those who wish to deal frequently, or in small
amounts of much less than Pounds 1,000, may well find that a self-select Pep
is more expensive than a managed Pep.
Paul Killik, of the stockbroking firm Killik, says, however, that Peps are
not the place to put speculative investments which you might want to buy and
sell quickly. Instead, he sees them as 'the place to tuck away good
long-term investments with reasonable yields.' David Nugent, of Pilling,
also regards Peps as a long-term investment. 'Go for blue-chip stocks with a
10-year view,' he advises.
Killik and Pilling are two of four plan managers recommended by Roz Barber
for their low dealing charges. The others are Reykers and Sharelink.
Killik (tel 071 224-2050) makes no initial charge or annual charges; and the
commission on dealings is 1.65 per cent, or a minimum of Pounds 40. Mr
Killik says it offers concessionary rates on 'bed and breakfast' shares - an
investor's existing shares can only be 'Pepped' if they are sold on the
market and bought again.
However, there is a dividend collection charge of Pounds 7.50. Mr Killik
points out that, if you deal in amounts of Pounds 2,400 or more, which is
the point at which 1.65 per cent becomes cheaper than the Pounds 40 minimum,
it is cheaper to have a self-select Pep. Dealing advice is also given at no
extra cost.
Pilling (061 832-6581) charges no initial or annual fees. Its commission
rate is 1.65 per cent, subject to a Pounds 30 minimum. The dividend
collection charge is Pounds 6.75, and advice is also part of the package.
Reykers (071 499-9097) lets you use your own stockbroker. There is a Pounds
40 initial fee, and a 1 per cent annual management fee which covers
collection and payment of dividends. Rates for a single-company self-select
Pep are a Pounds 20 initial fee and a 1 per cent annual management charge.
Investment advice is not given.
Sharelink (021 200 4545) makes an initial charge of Pounds 25, which is
being waived at the moment, and an annual administration fee of 0.75 per
cent of the value of the portfolio, subject to a minimum of Pounds 20. This
covers the dividend collection. Dealing charges are 1.5 per cent, with a
minimum of Pounds 17.50 and a maximum of Pounds 37.50 per order. No advice
is given.
Self-select Peps may prove more popular with the introduction this month of
the single-company Pep, which allows investors to take out a Pounds 3,000
Pep in addition to the Pounds 6,000 general Pep for any single tax year. If
you know that you want to buy and hold a particular company's shares, for
example, you should seriously consider using the self-select route, because
your investment dilemma is simplified by the need to select only that one
company.
Remember, however, that, for the vast majority of investors, it is the
exemption from income tax that is the most important advantage of a Pep.
This means that you should look for a stock which offers a healthy yield and
looks able to maintain its dividend.
There is one caveat for those wealthy investors who frequently face capital
gains tax bills, however. Losses on shares held in a Pep are arguably worse
than those held outside. Since there is no capital gains tax to pay on
shares held in a Pep, losses cannot be offset against CGT.
*Address and telephone number: see page 28
</TEXT>
