<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Survey of FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance - Personal
Equity Plans (23): Look at performance then at the spread - Unit Trusts /
Most investors should choose a trust with a high yield or the prospect of
dividend growth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNIT TRUST managers have been very grateful for the existence of personal
equity plans over the past couple of years.
Conventional unit trust sales have been hard to come by, given investor
caution following the 1987 crash and the 1990 Gulf crisis; and those few
small investors who have been persuaded into the equity market have recently
been enticed by the rival charms of investment trusts.
Net sales of unit trusts (gross sales less redemptions) in 1990 were just
Pounds 392m, and even the figure for the first 10 months of 1991 (Pounds
2.61bn) was well down on 1987's record of Pounds 6.33bn.
But sales of unit trust Peps have been growing strongly - from Pounds 310m
in 1989 to Pounds 498m in 1990, and Pounds 520m in the first three-quarters
of 1991. And Pep investments are highly stable, with monthly repurchases
running at only 12 per cent of sales in 1991, compared with a 72 per cent
repurchase rate on overall trust sales.
A big attraction - and selling point - for unit trust Peps is that they
rarely involve any additional charges. So if you are going to buy a unit
trust anyway, there is little reason not to buy one in Pep form and receive
your income and capital gains tax-free.
But the advantages of a Pep only become significant over the long term. Past
figures from the Unit Trust Association suggest that the Pep investor
placing Pounds 1,000 in the average unit trust would have beaten his fellow
non-Pep unitholder by around 50 per cent over 15 years and 100 per cent over
25.
The reason why it takes so long for Pep gains to come through is that, for
most investors, it is the income tax, rather than the capital gains tax,
exemption that is important. With capital gains tax exemption at Pounds
5,500 per individual per year, and with indexation allowed on post-1982
investments, few unitholders are likely to face a capital gains tax bill.
Most investors pay income tax at 25 or 40 per cent. But on a Pounds 3,000
investment, even a trust with a 5 per cent yield would pay an annual income
of only Pounds 150. So the potential tax saving in the first year would be
Pounds 60 for top-rate payers and just Pounds 37.50 for those on the basic
rate. Eventually, and with the help of reinvestment, this tax saving will
grow into a substantial sum.
The fact that Pep repurchases are so low - only Pounds 28.7m in the third
quarter of 1991 - indicates that investors have absorbed this lesson of
long-termism.
But it also means that most private investors must make yield a prime
consideration in choosing a unit trust Pep. A trust with a high yield, or
one with the prospect of substantial dividend growth, is the way to make the
best use of the tax advantages. Only those who frequently pay capital gains
tax should opt for a high-growth, low-yield Pep.
These calculations may change, of course, if a Labour government is elected
this year. An increase in the top rate of income tax to 50 per cent would
heighten the attractions of high-yielding trusts; a decrease in the CGT
threshold (and an increase in top rate CGT) would raise the allure of growth
trusts.
Otherwise, when choosing a unit trust Pep, investors have only two real
criteria they can use. The first is performance - and the important
consideration here is not to be seduced merely by short-term (one year or
less) growth. Remember that it is only in the long term that a Pep
investment will really pay off.
Look for consistency of performance over longer periods - there are tables
ranking unit trusts over five years at the back of this Review. The FT's
sister publication, Money Management magazine, carries performance
statistics every month.
Experts generally agree that first-time investors should stick to trusts
investing in the UK. Those who want to invest overseas should start with the
international funds rather than opt for the more volatile specialist country
funds.
The second criteria is to look at the spread between offer and bid prices
(the prices at which you buy and sell). The greater the spread, the more
your investment will have to grow to get your money back. Spreads tend to
vary between 5 and 9 per cent. If the performance records of two trusts are
equal, it is usually best to opt for the fund with the lower spread.
Larger investors may be put off unit trust Peps by the government's Pounds
3,000 limit on collective-fund plans (and Pounds 1,500 on those trusts
without 50 per cent of their assets in Europe). Investment trusts have been
able to sidestep the rule through the new-issue market, a route not open to
unit trusts.
Instead, unit trust managers have offered top-up schemes, in which Pounds
3,000 goes into the trust and the remainder into individual shares, but this
dilutes the diversification principle, which is one of the main attractions
of collective funds.
Investors need to check carefully that the top-up element is not spread so
widely as to incur substantial dealing costs. And if they are not likely to
pay capital gains tax, they should also ensure that the top-up investments
offer a decent enough yield to take advantage of the income tax exemption.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXII Photograph Cast your bread upon the waters, small investors
should look to the long term (Omitted).
</PAGE>
