<PROFILE>_AN-CAXBAADYFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920124
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Survey of FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance - Personal
Equity Plans (22): Don't let the tax tail wag the dog - How to pick them /
Investors should ask themselves two crucial questions when looking at the
charges levied on the different forms of Pep on the market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT IS tempting to buy anything that has a 'tax-free' label on it.
All other things being equal, you should indeed save tax. But all other
things are usually not equal. So do not commit the cardinal sin of 'letting
the tax tail wag the investment dog'.
This can easily happen when investing in Peps. They are free of both income
and capital gains tax, so you cannot ask for more tax efficiency. But they
cost a lot to administer.
In the early years of the Pep scheme, when only Pounds 2,400 could be put
into a plan, investors soon became disenchanted. Attempts at active
portfolio management with sums this small were doomed to failure. Minimum
dealing charges of maybe Pounds 30 or Pounds 40, when switching between
holdings of around Pounds 400, made it almost impossible to make a profit,
let alone deliver the full value of the tax incentive.
Understanding of Peps is now more sophisticated.
But you must ask yourself two questions before looking at the charges levied
on the different Peps on the market.
What is your own tax position? You only need to pay capital gains tax if you
sell shares or other securities for gains, after indexation, of more than
Pounds 5,500 in one tax year. Thus you need to be a very keen, or wealthy,
private investor before it will apply to you. If there is no realistic
chance of your paying any CGT in the near future, the exemption from income
tax is the only relief you will receive.
What investments do you already hold? If you do not have much money salted
away in long-term investments, then diversification within your Pep takes a
high priority. But if you have a large equity portfolio, you will probably
have to pay CGT, and Peps must be judged using different criteria.
Taking these considerations in turn, people who do not pay CGT should look
first at the income, or yield, from a Pep. Growth is important, of course,
but they are not buying extra tax concessions by paying for the
administrative charges of a Pep manager. Instead, they are cutting their
potential gain, by paying so much of the initial investment on Pep charges.
David Wells, of accountants BDO Binder Hamlyn, illustrates the costs and
benefits of the tax savings as follows. Typical opening charges on a Pounds
6,000 Pep would be 5 per cent, plus VAT, plus a 0.2 per cent commission for
buying the shares. This comes to Pounds 363.80.
A direct purchase of shares might cost around 1.75 per cent in commission,
according to Mr Wells. This would only knock Pounds 105 off the initial
investment.
These figures in themselves should dampen the spirits of people planning to
use Peps to invest for growth.
Next, Mr Wells looked at annual management charges, which are typically 1
per cent, plus VAT. This comes to Pounds 70.50.
'You need a tax saving of at least that amount to justify the extra cost of
having a Pep,' he says. That means that this Pep would need a yield of 3.13
per cent before the savings in income tax for a 40 per cent taxpayer
outbalanced the extra costs.
If you only pay 25 per cent income tax then you need a higher yield before a
Pep becomes worthwhile.
Mr Wells' conclusion is clear: 'The emphasis of our Pep recommendations
should be on income-orientated plans with low initial charges. Higher
charges may, of course, be justified by superior performance, but this will
be proved only with hindsight.'
This rigorous approach is a good antidote for those who leap at the
'tax-free' label. Considerations such as these have led to a breed of
'high-yield' or 'income' Peps. They achieve their yield by combining a group
of high-yielding equities (those which have particularly high dividends in
relation to the share price) with income shares of split-capital investment
trusts.
Roz Barder, editor of Chase De Vere's Pep Guide, says that a 6 per cent
yield for an income Pep is typical, although some more speculative plans may
be able to offer yields approaching 10 per cent. These yields are good, but
Mr Wells' figures show that they are far from spectacular.
If you do not already hold a large variety of investments, then a Pep
investing in unit or investment trusts makes sense. You are only allowed to
put Pounds 3,000 into one of these Peps (except for new issues), which may
be a disadvantage, but you automatically buy into a wide spread of equities.
Past performance tables allow you to make an informed choice of fund
manager.
Most important, the vast majority of unit trust Peps, according to Ms
Barder, make no extra charge for investing via a Pep than they would if you
invested direct. Few charge more than an extra percentage point. If you
wanted to invest up to Pounds 3,000 in a unit trust anyway, then this neatly
delivers you from the agonies of choice - there is no point in not making
the investment via a Pep.
Finally, if you regularly need to pay CGT, and have an existing portfolio of
equities, then Peps are best approached as a tax-free 'pocket' for part of
your portfolio. Before the end of each tax year, transfer up to your maximum
allocation into a 'self-select' Pep.
You only need look at one criterion here - charges. The less the annual and
initial charges, the better the Pep will be.
The joker in the pack of all these careful calculations is the possibility
of a Labour government. As reported on page 4 of this Review, Labour has not
ruled out retaining Peps, but it has also not ruled out abolishing them. It
has pledged to honour tax reliefs on all plans opened before it takes
office.
Higher top rates of tax, which Labour has pledged to introduce, might make
Peps a handy tax shelter. All their advantages, for those in the top income
tax band, would automatically be increased. A cut in the threshold before
CGT is paid would also make Peps more valuable.
These are cogent arguments. But none of them provides any reason to pay more
in charges than you have to.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-12811</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CAXBAADXFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920124
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Survey of FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance - Personal
Equity Plans (21): If they go, they won't go quietly - Peps offer a tax
shelter in which a married couple could by now have amassed joint portfolios
of over Pounds 50,000. A pre-election boom seems likely, as Labour threatens
to end them; so . . .
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JUST WHEN new opportunities are opening up in personal equity plans, the
threat of political change looms large with the impending general election.
But the Pep industry is gearing up for a pre-election boom. If Peps go, they
will not go quietly.
The personal equity plan was introduced by Mr Nigel Lawson, then chancellor
of the exchequer, at the beginning of 1987. Peps formed part of the drive
towards 'popular capitalism', which also involved incentives for small
investors to buy shares in privatised companies.
But it has always proved difficult to match up the political inspiration
behind Peps with the administrative reality of running tax-sheltered savings
plans of a fairly modest size. The Inland Revenue has insisted on imposing a
bureaucratic structure of approved plan managers, to guard against abuse.
But that has brought a heavy cost penalty.
Ordinarily, private individuals who invest in shares face a big tax burden.
They pay income tax at 25 or 40 per cent on dividends, and capital gains tax
 -also at up to 40 per cent - on any gains of over Pounds 5,500 in any
single tax year.
The personal equity plan, however, offers total protection from income tax
and capital gains tax. The income and capital gains can roll up tax-free.
Over a period of years this can have a powerful effect in boosting the
overall returns.
It sounds simple and attractive, but for several years the Treasury dithered
over how big to make the plans, and over the details of their contents. The
politicians wanted millions of people of relatively modest means to use Peps
to hold small parcels of shares in British companies. But the marketing
reality was that Peps would not succeed in pulling in really large sums
until relatively wealthy people could use them to hold significantly large
portfolios, and moreover could invest conveniently in collective funds (that
is, unit trusts and investment trusts) rather than in individual companies.
So, after Pounds 480m had been invested in Peps in 1987, demand collapsed to
Pounds 200m in 1988. Originally only Pounds 2,400 could be invested in an
annual plan, and of that just Pounds 540 could go into collective funds.
Subsequently, however, the scope has been greatly extended. Standard plans
now range up to a maximum of Pounds 6,000, of which Pounds 3,000 can go into
collective funds. In the 1990-91 tax year, 500,000 plans were taken out,
worth Pounds 1.6bn, or an average of Pounds 3,200 each. In all, over Pounds
4bn has been invested so far.
Interest has remained high. Investment trust companies, for instance, have
discovered a loophole in the Pep rules, so that the whole Pounds 6,000 can
be invested when a new trust is floated. This was successfully exploited,
for instance, when M &amp; G launched its Income Investment Trust last autumn.
Half of the Pounds 246m issue was 'pepped'.
From the beginning of this year, too, an extra Pounds 3,000 allowance can be
applied to a single-company Pep. These are restrictive vehicles, which may
be more useful for employee shareholders than for the public at large, but
nevertheless many companies are arranging facilities for the public to hold
their shares in this tax-efficient way.
One final significant change is being brought in. Until now, shares in Peps
have been limited to those of British companies, but in future companies in
other European Community member states will qualify, too.
What it all adds up to is that, from modest beginnings, the personal equity
plan has grown into a substantial and reasonably flexible tax shelter for
investments. A married couple can invest Pounds 18,000 between them this
financial year. If they had used up their maximum entitlements since the
beginning in 1987, they could have amassed joint portfolios of over Pounds
50,000, with another Pounds 18,000 investible from April 6.
The real significance of this could become evident if the Labout party wins
the coming general election. Labour has said it will abolish new plans, but
existing Peps will be permitted to run on indefinitely, benefiting as before
from tax exemptions.
At present, the tax advantages are marginal for most people. Although the
income tax relief is worth, say, 2 per cent in extra dividend yield to a
higher rate taxpayer, Pep charges will cancel out at least half of this.
Standard rate payers probably do not benefit at all, compared with holding
shares directly.
As for capital gains tax, few people at present pay it. With a little care,
and with some calculated bed-and-breakfasting, the Pounds 5,500 exemption
limit (Pounds 11,000 for a couple) will suffice.
But under Labour it could be very different, especially for the wealthy. The
top rate of tax on dividends is set to shoot up to 59 per cent, and there
would probably be a 50 per cent rate of capital gains tax on all profits
above a reduced exemption limit. Suddenly Peps would become very valuable
tax shelters indeed.
There may not be any need to rush. New Peps would not be abolished
immediately on a Labour victory - there would have to be a Budget - and
Labour might not win anyway.
Still, unit trust companies in particular will be hoping to benefit from any
flurry this spring. In the first nine months of 1991, net sales of unit
trust Peps amounted to Pounds 520m, possibly something like half of all unit
trust sales direct to the public.
But some unit trust groups have found Peps very difficult to administer,
especially if they offer Pounds 3,000 direct-share portfolios to top up the
Pounds 3,000 unit trust maximum to Pounds 6,000. One or two have been
heavily fined by Imro, the investment management regulatory body, for
failing to keep the details of the accounts in order.
What was originally intended to be a simple tax incentive has turned into
costly bureaucratic tangle. But if there is a change of government the
personal equity plan may yet achieve its period of fufilment, albeit in
circumstances which its Tory creators would not have chosen.
 -----------------------------------------
PEPS' PROGRESS
 -----------------------------------------
                     Number
                    of plans     Amount
                     ('000s)   (Poundsm)
 -----------------------------------------
1987                   270         480
1988                   120         200
1989-90 (15 months)    580       1,600
1990-91                500       1,600
 -----------------------------------------
Source: Inland Revenue
