<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Survey of FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (20): Balm
for home-buyers but it's hardly generous - What's new? / Citibank has begun
adding two years' free unemployment cover to its mortgages
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARBARA ELLIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNCERTAINTY HAS been a noticeable feature of many recent arrivals on the
personal finance market.
Lacking any single obvious successor to last year's Tessas, companies have
had to concentrate on calming the recession-shredded nerves of investors and
borrowers.
This month, Citibank has begun adding two years' free unemployment cover to
all its mortgages taken out by people aged between 21 and 60.
The insurance covers the original level of the mortgage instalment, up to a
maximum of Pounds 1,000 per month, replacing up to 12 months' payments after
a 60-day waiting period from the time the borrower becomes unemployed. The
waiting period can be cut to 30 days if the borrower buys additional
accident and sickness cover, priced at between Pounds 3 and Pounds 3.50 per
Pounds 100 of the monthly payment to be protected.
This offer is not particularly generous, bearing in mind Citibank's Pounds
250 arrangement fee, and interest penalties on early redemption of all
mortgages. A number of lenders will provide cover against accident and
sickness, as well as unemployment, for between Pounds 4.50 and Pounds 5.50
per Pounds 100 of the monthly payment. Housebuilders such as Croudace have
also been offering up to three years' free payment protection.
*****
LURING CAUTIOUS investors away from building society accounts is a constant
goal for investment managers, and Irish Life is the latest to attempt this,
by providing a partial guarantee.
The company is offering a single-premium insurance bond for a minimum of
Pounds 2,000, guaranteeing return of the capital on August 1, 1996, plus any
growth achieved. Investors effectively pay for the guarantee, through an
initial 5 per cent and an annual 1.25 per cent charge. The guarantee does
not apply to bonds cashed in before August 1, 1996.
The guaranteed bond is to be linked to Irish Life's managed fund. Over the
five years to December 6, 1991, Irish Life Global Managed 3 ranked 34th out
of 135 managed funds monitored by Finstat, showing a gain of 35.7 per cent,
compared with the 85.7 per cent put on by Family Assurance Concentrated
Growth.
Over one year to December 6, Irish Life Universal Equity ranked 94th out of
176 UK equity managed funds, gaining 5.2 per cent, compared with Aetna Life
Special Opportunities' top gain of 28.9 per cent.
If recent trends continue, investors would seem to stand a good chance of
better performance from a non-guaranteed bond.
*****
SUN LIFE can hardly make reassuring noises about the Pacific Growth
Portfolio unit trust it is due to launch at the beginning of February.
Concentrating on the main Pacific markets, but excluding Japan, the
portfolio will initially include mainly Hong Kong, Singapore and Australia,
moving on to Taiwan (when accessible to foreign investors), New Zealand and
eventually China.
Nick Wells, of Sun Life, uses the traditional 'not for widows and orphans'
description of the unit trust, which is to have a minimum lump-sum
investment level of Pounds 1,000 and a regular monthly savings plan taking
Pounds 25. Charges are to be 5.75 per cent initially and 1 1/2 per cent
annually.
'People should have a small part of their portfolio in this area on a
longer-term view - five years-plus, but look for a relatively bumpy ride,'
said Mr Wells, noting that fund manager Pamela Chan, based in London, would
be trying to iron out as many of the jolts as possible.
Sun Life is also re-organising money already under management, to make sure
that the new fund starts with at least Pounds 20m. 'With the confidence
level as it is, certainly in the UK, most investors will probably stick
where they are,' said Mr Wells. 'We can't guarantee success in terms of
performance, but we can give the fund the opportunity of getting off to a
reasonable start, with a size of portfolio you can manage and run.'
*****
INVESTORS used to the idea that risks should be spread by diversifying
investments may have misgivings about the concept of single-company personal
equity plans. But investment managers are finding different ways around such
objections.
Brokers Henderson Crosthwaite say they see their single-company Pep being
taken out only by people who already have a general Pep (with Henderson
Crosthwaite). The firm is offering two versions of the plan: self-selected,
with a 1 per cent annual charge, and discretionary with a 1 1/4 per cent
annual charge.
During the launch period, which ends next Friday, January 31, the initial
charge on either type of plan is Pounds 15 plus VAT, with a minimum
investment of Pounds 1,000 and minimum commission on dealings of Pounds 10.
After that date, the minimum investment goes up to Pounds 1,500, the initial
charge to Pounds 30 plus VAT, and dealing commission to 1.5 per cent or a
minimum of Pounds 25.
*****
LLOYDS BANK has three varieties of single-company Pep, with shares to be
selected from a list of 100 blue-chip companies based on, but not limited
to, the FT-SE 100.
Charges on all the plans are an annual fee of Pounds 20 plus VAT. Dealings
done on bulk dealing dates selected by Lloyds are charged at 0.2 per cent,
but investors who deal at other times pay 1.65 per cent, or a minimum of
Pounds 25. The bank also charges an administration fee of Pounds 10 for
switches.
The cheapest of the three uses one plan continuing over several years.
Investors open the plan, either with the full Pounds 3,000 allowed by the
Revenue, or with Pounds 300, to which they may add in instalments of at
least Pounds 100. In each succeeding year, the investor can then put up to
another Pounds 3,000 into the same company's shares, or move the complete
holding into another company.
Alternatively, the investor can open a separate plan each year, either
keeping to the same company each time, or choosing a different company year
by year.
Stand by for the BES's big clearance sale: The Budget is likely to end
buy-back schemes: see Back Page
</TEXT>
