<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Survey of FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (14):
Enthusiasts may spoil the scenery - Investment Trusts / Still the new issues
come. Can the good times last, or will supply exceed demand?
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IS THE investment trust industry over-doing it? The recent enthusiasm of
private investors for the sector has provoked a flurry of new issues, many
of them linked to personal equity plans. Eventually this supply will
overwhelm demand. The question is: when?
It might have been thought M&amp;G's success in raising Pounds 246m for its
income trust last year would have soaked up the bulk of private-investor
demand. Obviously, even M&amp;G did not think so and it is launching yet another
trust - based on its Recovery fund.
And another major trust is currently being launched - the Fleming Income and
Capital Investment Trust. Fleming is aiming for a minimum of Pounds 50m,
with a possible maximum of Pounds 250m.
Like many other recent trust launches, Fleming Income and Capital has a
split structure, with zero dividend (for steady capital appreciation) and
ordinary income (for yield and a geared capital performance) shares. The
hope is that the split structure will prevent the trust from trading at a
discount - traditionally the great barrier to investment-trust new issues.
The trust will aim for an overall yield of 6.9 per cent, which will result
in a yield on the ordinary income shares of 9.3 per cent - highly attractive
if they can be held in a Pep. And, indeed, the trust is deliberately
launched at a time to exploit a loophole in the Pep rules - a full Pounds
6,000 of shares can be placed in a Pep in each of the 1991-92 and 1992-93
tax years.
The enthusiasm for investment trusts has been supported by their manifest
outperformance of unit trusts over the past few years. However, it is
doubtful whether this is repeatable. A large part of the share-price
outperformance has been attributable to the narrowing of the discount to net
assets on which shares trade. In a neatly virtuous circle, the narrowing of
the discount has, in turn, been prompted by the return of the private
investor.
Although it is arguable that the discount will not widen to its old levels
of over 25 per cent, there is less scope for it to narrow further. Many
trusts still have institutional shareholders which are willing sellers.
In addition, investment trusts are also losing part of their cost edge over
their unitised rivals, now that trusts are paying 3 per cent commissions to
advisers.
Risk is also a factor. Investors who have bought some of the recent
split-capital issues may not understand the nature of the risk/reward
profile of their shares; and the fact that the discount may widen, and that
investment trusts can 'gear up' by borrowing, may also have eluded them.
In short, there is a danger that investment trusts will suffer the 'tourist
syndrome'. They were delightful havens when only few people knew about them;
but now that they have been discovered by the whole world, they may get
spoiled by over-development.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XVI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-12818</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CAXBAADQFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920124
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Survey of FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (15):
Boldly go but get the right guide - Emerging markets look tempting, and a
trust can cut the risk
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A STRIKING feature of the 1991 investment trust league tables was the strong
performance of funds based in emerging markets.
The best trust of the year was Latin American, and emerging markets funds
from Templeton and Beta Global were in fourth and sixth place respectively.
The argument in favour of investing in emerging markets is simply put.
Economic growth rates in such countries are higher, and this should
translate into higher corporate earnings growth rates. In addition, the
underdevelopment of stock markets in such countries can offer greater
opportunity for picking 'bargain' stocks - since fewer analysts are looking
at the markets.
The risks involved are likely to be substantial, however. Many emerging
markets owe their prosperity to a limited number of commodities or
industries - and thus can be vulnerable to a sudden downturn in demand in
that sector. In addition, the number of companies available for investment
is limited, as is the liquidity in those companies' shares.
Investment trust managers have two counter-arguments. The first is that
their closed-end structure gives them protection from a sudden downturn. If
share prices fall suddenly, an open-ended fund, such as a unit trust, would
face redemptions from investors trying to cut their losses. To meet these
redemptions, the managers would have to sell shares; in illiquid emerging
markets, that would mean accepting rock-bottom prices.
An investment trust can simply sit tight through a downturn; if shareholders
want to realise their investments, they must find another buyer. The result
is that unit trusts shrink in bear markets; investment trust shares simply
sink to a discount. This should make it easier for investment trust managers
to outperform over the long term; although shareholders who buy when trusts
are at a premium and then sell when the discount is widest will not see the
benefit.
The second argument is that, while individual emerging markets may be risky,
trusts can reduce the dangers by investing across a range of countries. Mark
Mobius, the manager of Templeton Emerging Markets, says the trust is already
invested in 18 countries and is interested in backing many more over the
long term.
A global recession could affect a large number of emerging countries at the
same time - as was illustrated in the early 1980s by the international debt
crisis. But Mr Mobius reckons that his trust can still pick individual
stocks which will prosper.
That said, the success of many of these funds may depend on the asset
allocation skills of the managers - those that picked Latin America last
year did very well; those with a large exposure to, say, Thailand, will not
have prospered so much.
Picking the right manager could therefore be even more important than in
most sectors.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XVI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-12819</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CAXBAADPFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920124
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Survey of FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (13):
Mauled in the market - The Professionals / UK equities have election nerves,
but the five see value elsewhere in Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This feature is not a competition, but an allocation exercise, the purpose
of which is to see how five professional fund managers manage a Pounds
250,000 portfolio on behalf of a hypothetical client of their choice. In
each case, the client is assumed to be either a wealthy individual or a
small self-administered pension fund. All the fund managers emphasise that
they are investing for the long term (10 years or more) rather than for
short-term gain. The exercise started at the beginning of October 1990. The
portfolios given here were drawn up as at the end of December, and will be
reviewed again at the end of March.
OUR PROFESSIONALS have, perhaps inevitably, been mauled along with the
majority by the equity market reversals of the past quarter.
Worst hit were Gartmore, where Paul Myners' 5 per cent holding in Japanese
warrants languishes at 60 per cent of its October value. Gartmore face an
approximate loss for the quarter of 7 per cent.
At Mercury, Simon Toynbee concedes that he jumped the gun by raising his UK
equity exposure in October to 60 per cent of the portfolio. With the UK
market falling by almost 9 per cent on the quarter, his portfolio slipped by
nearly 6 per cent. David Poole, at Singer &amp; Friedlander, also had 61 per
cent of his portfolio invested in the UK, and so lost about 6 per cent on
the quarter.
Damage limitation was achieved most effectively by Douglas McDougall, at
Baillie Gifford. He had a smaller exposure to the UK market, and was helped
by a 15 per cent holding in the south-east Asian markets, and excellent
performance by French bonds, also 15 per cent of the portfolio. The fall in
his portfolio was probably no more than 4 1/2 per cent.
Howard Beaufort, at Newton, also earned a late reward for having remained
consistently more bearish than his counterparts. Like Baillie Gifford,
Newton's portfolio had limited exposure to the UK, and saw benefit from a 12
per cent holding in French bonds. He might have limited losses even more
effectively than Baillie Gifford, had it not been for a large US stake and a
drab performance in Europe, in particular Sweden.
In view of Mr Beaufort's past bearishness, it is worth noting a change in
his tone concerning the UK: 'For the first time in 15 months, I have taken
my bullish hat and coat out of the wardrobe and am giving them a brushing
down,' he notes. 'The next few weeks will almost certainly prove to be a
rough ride, but opportunities will therefore present themselves in the first
quarter.'
Looking into 1992, most are now agreed that the UK will remain nervous ahead
of a general election, and vulnerable to a possible reversal in the US. They
see good value elsewhere in Europe, though views divide strongly over
prospects for Germany.
No one foresees fresh blood on the Tokyo markets, but nor do any yet see
good enough values to justify buying interest. They also agree that Hong
Kong and south-east Asia offer the brightest short-term market prospects.
Loyalty to bonds remains strong, particularly the French bonds that have
served them so well so far this year. Yields average 8.8 per cent at
present, which is attractive when inflation there is below 3 per cent.
Douglas McDougall, at Baillie Gifford, plans no changes in the balance of
his portfolio. The imminent general election in the UK makes him nervous
about raising exposure to the market, even though it is 'fairly valued'.
Remaining optimistic about prospects for Germany, where he sees the east
beginning to recover, and interest rates likely to be cut before July, he
stands behind his 25 per cent European holding.
Paul Myners, at Gartmore, proposes to sell his remaining Yen cash to buy
equities in Europe, where he sees his 'favourite markets after Asia'. His
European market holding rises to 15 per cent, with emphasis on the
Netherlands and France. The Pacific Rim holdings stay at 12.5 per cent.
In the UK, which will continue to account for half of the portfolio, he
favours growth and smaller stocks. Japanese warrants are to be held,
'despite poor performance', in the hope of capturing leveraged recovery when
the Tokyo market turns upward. The US offers 'dubious value' at present, but
may offer buying opportunities as pundits over-react to bad news.
Simon Toynbee, at Mercury Asset Management, plans to trim cash holdings from
9 per cent to 7 per cent, using the funds to lift holdings in Europe. The
portfolio otherwise remains unchanged. Having paid a price for increasing
his UK holdings 'prematurely' in October, he does not plan to dilute the
holding. In spite of uncertainty until Wall Street rallies, he sees UK
corporate earnings recovering sharply late in 1992. With one third of the
portfolio outside the UK market, he feels hedged against falls which might
occur if the Labour party wins the general election.
Howard Beaufort, at Newton Investment Management, plans to cut his US
holding from 12 per cent to 8 per cent of the portfolio, and to lift UK
holdings by 4 per cent to 44 per cent. The portfolio otherwise remains
unchanged.
Mr Beaufort is gloomy about the US, where renewed weakness 'is a strong
near-term possibility'. The UK will also be fragile, but he feels that it
will be 'far more justifiable for markets to adopt a bullish stance' in the
opening months of 1992.
Elsewhere in Europe, he sees Germany 'likely to remain under a cloud', but
feels more bullish about the French markets. He remains nervous about Japan,
but sees support at present depressed levels.
David Poole, at Singer &amp; Friedlander, plans to trim US holdings still
further, while adding to European bonds and buying some sterling cash. In
the UK, 'significant weakness in oversold stocks has been used to buy'.
Seeing the markets of continental Europe impeded by Germany's high interest
rates, he foresees a recovery as rates fall in spring. He nevertheless warns
that Russian unrest and German wage demands 'remain the caveat to recovery'.
Sentiment is negative on the US, where high equity prices are 'discounting a
considerable recovery which does not appear to be happening'. By contrast,
he believes that Japan now offers 'fundamental value', and predicts
'outperformance in 1992'. Rueing his limited exposure to the rest of Asia,
Mr Poole pinpoints Hong Kong as 'an attractive and undervalued market' in
spite of the shadow cast by 1997.
