<DOCNO>FT921-12822</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CAXBAADMFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920124
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Survey of FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (10): An
honest man bides his time - Gestetner has taken a tumble. But in a general
price fall, the good tends to go down with the bad and the over-priced
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN GOLDSTEIN-JACKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
YOU ARE an honest man, a man of integrity,' said the Chinese soothsayer at
Wong Tai Sin Temple, in Hong Kong. He had been trying to bend back my
thumbs. As the thumbs remained straight and unbent this was, supposedly, a
sign of utmost honesty.
As a result of trying to live up to the soothsayer's expectations, I have
saved a lot of money.
Shares that are mentioned favourably by newspaper columnists quite often
rise in price, as a result of market makers expecting people to follow those
recommendations (and thus marking up the price) and/or people actually
buying the shares. Sometimes, after an initial flurry of interest, the share
price falls back again as earlier investors take profits.
In the autumn Quarterly Review, I selected shares in two companies
(Gestetner and Taveners) for a capital growth portfolio. At that time, I did
not personally own any shares in Gestetner, and I stated that for 'ethical
reasons' I would not buy any Gestetner shares 'until at least one week after
the publication' of the article. This was intended to demonstrate that I
would not be investing in Gestetner in such a way that I could profit from
having mentioned the shares in an article.
However, within days of that article's being published, Gestetner issued a
profits warning. The shares fell by 19.3 per cent within a week - the second
greatest price fall of any UK company during that week] My self-denying
ordnance had thus saved me from a considerable loss.
By December, Gestetner shares had fallen to a low of 108p, compared with the
portfolio's 'purchase' price of 183p.
Of course, in the 'real world', on the announcement of a dramatic downturn
in profits, the portfolio would have cut its losses and sold the Gestetner
shares and thus limited its loss to around 20p per share, and then perhaps
bought back the shares at a much lower level. The quarterly portfolio,
however, can only buy or sell if a clear indication is given in an article
as to the likely buying or selling price. As I had not anticipated such a
sharp drop in Gestetner share price, I had not mentioned in my article the
possibility of selling the shares. Thus, the portfolio was stuck with them.
Why had I not foreseen Gestetner's downturn in profits? Probably for some of
the same reasons that encouraged Ricoh, the Japanese office automation
equipment maker, to pay 250p per share for a 24.2 per cent stake in the
company last September: the company appeared to be trading quite well and
had good long-term prospects with a worldwide spread of interests.
As mentioned in the autumn issue, the portfolio purchased Gestetner shares
taking a five-year view: either its profits would eventually be enhanced by
its relationship with Ricoh, or Ricoh might make a takeover bid.
In December, Gestetner announced its results for its financial year to
October 31. Pre-tax profits had fallen by 57 per cent. According to a report
in the FT, Gestetner's finance director had said that the profits' shortfall
was caused by second-half sales being well below budget and 'management
mistakes, notably a late reaction to faltering sales, had contributed to the
decline'.
Gestetner's chairman stated that the recession had also affected profits, as
had a rationalisation of activities which had resulted in job losses for 10
per cent of the company's workforce.
I still view Gestetner as a 'long-term hold' - although Ricoh's own pre-tax
profits for the six months to end September, 1991, fell by 58.5 per cent.
On December 24, my personal pension scheme bought some Gestetner shares,
paying 114p a share. I was interested to see from the FT of December 28 that
one of Gestetner's directors had purchased 100,000 shares in the company
that month so, hopefully, this augurs well for the future. And surely Ricoh
will want to see Gestetner's shares improve to much nearer the price it paid
for its original stake in the company.
My other recommendation in the autumn Review was for Taveners. The portfolio
'bought' the shares for 70p each, and they are now around 80p. Judging by
the number of marshmallows my wife and youngest daughter ate during
Christmas, this marshmallow and boiled-sweet manufacturer ought to have
reasonable prospects. The takeover potential remains, with Finnish
confectionery group Karl Fazer owning 29.89 per cent of the company. Again,
the portfolio takes a longer-term view. My personal pension scheme still
retains its small Taveners shareholding.
The portfolio started out with Pounds 10,000 in cash and invested Pounds
5,195 of it, with the remainder being placed in Britannia Building Society
Capital Trust.
I have debated long and hard whether the portfolio ought to make further
equity investments or keep cash on deposit. I still believe that shares in
many companies in the UK and US are far too high and that a market
correction - either sudden or a gradual downwards movement - will happen
within the next 12 months.
The 500 companies in the US Standard and Poor's index now have an average
price-earnings ratio of over 20 - whereas 10 years ago the average was just
over 8.
With a general election in the UK, presidential elections in the US,
uncertainties and major problems in eastern Europe, the Middle East and
elsewhere, who can say with certainty what will happen to share prices? And
during a general share-price fall, the 'good' usually falls with the
over-priced and the 'bad'.
I like a number of companies - such as United Biscuits and the
photograph-booth operator Photo-Me, in the UK, and Dole Food, in the US  -
but not at current share price levels.
I considered the portfolio taking a risky, quick in-and-out gamble in the
hope of rapidly making up the losses made by its Gestetner investment. For
example, at the time of writing, shares in Regina (the 'Royal Jelly' firm)
are 1.75p, yet in the chairman's December 5 statement in the annual report,
he says that the company 'has paid off all its bank borrowings in the UK . .
. and, save for a small loan in Ireland, the group has no borrowings'. The
group has reversed its negative cash position and sales have 'stabilised'.
But an investment on a 'quick in-and-out' basis would not be for the
cautious, and so I am not recommending or including it in the portfolio.
With increased attention being focused on Spain this year, as host to the
Olympics and Expo '92, I had hoped that there would be a choice of major
investment trusts available which specialised in Spanish investment. Sadly,
all I could find was the First Spanish Investment Trust.
While the company is no doubt soundly managed, at the time of writing, its
interim results for 1991-92 had not been announced, and it needs a close
inspection of these results before an investment could be contemplated.
Its July 1991 annual report stated that the net asset value had fallen by
11.2 per cent, while the Madrid Stock Exchange index had decreased by 3.6
per cent in sterling terms over a similar period.
I am also somewhat concerned that the trust's list of holdings, at May 31,
1991, had 20.31 per cent of its holdings in Spanish banking shares and 30
per cent in Spanish construction and property shares.
The portfolio would certainly be interested in investing in the flotation of
Britain's biggest venture capital group, 3i, due later this year - but only
if the price was right.
Thus, the portfolio retains its shares in Gestetner and Taveners, and keeps
money on deposit ready to invest in attractive opportunities as they arise
and for the possible purchase of shares in 3i.
