<PROFILE>_AN-CAXBAADJFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920124
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Survey of FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (9): The
Sheep went astray, and Monkey business may be subdued
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE YEAR of the Sheep failed to bring the Tokyo stock market the peace and
calm that are symbolic of the sign. Instead, the Gulf war, stock scandals
and Red Monday hit a market already reeling from the sharp falls experienced
in 1990.
The last quarter of 1991 offered no cheer. In October, the big four brokers
(Nomura, Daiwa, Nikko and Yamaichi) did penance for their loss-compensation
to favoured clients, allegations of stock-price manipulation and connections
with gangsters, by suspending business at branches for up to six weeks.
While the Nikkei stock average managed to close the year on a positive note,
thanks to the surprise cut in the official discount rate on the last day of
trading for 1991, it remained 3.8 per cent lower from the end of the third
quarter, and down 4.5 per cent on the year.
Average daily turnover remained below 300m shares during the fourth quarter,
and turnover for the year fell to 91.7bn shares, the lowest since 1982.
Individual investors, disgusted with the special treatment of larger
institutional investors, continued to sell off holdings, moving to
investments with secured returns. This, in turn, squeezed the flow of new
money into investment-trust funds, active traders in the stock market.
The spate of poor interim corporate profits, announced during October,
clearly reflected the slowdown of the Japanese economy, adding to the
pessimism among investors.
The active buying by foreign investors, which had supported share prices in
the third quarter, gradually faded, and selling by domestic investors at
higher levels prevented shares from rising.
Meanwhile, in contrast to the sluggishness in the cash market, trading in
the stock futures market boomed. Arbitrage activity between the futures and
cash stock market grew to record highs, prompting authorities to blame
futures-related trading for the volatility in the cash stock market.
With the Year of the Monkey, the Tokyo stock market has entered its third
year of weakness, the longest post-war correction period.
Forecasts of a recovery remain mixed, and although further cuts of the
discount rate by the Bank of Japan are expected this quarter to help
business confidence, some fund managers point out that lower interest rates
will not necessarily mean higher prices.
In the Pacific Basin, Hong Kong remained firm during the fourth quarter, and
was one of the best performers of the year, rising over 40 per cent. Despite
increasing inflation, the currency's linkage to the US dollar has caused
interest rates to fall, resulting in excess funds flowing into property and
equity investments.
Although the Australian market faltered in the last three months of 1991, on
the year it gained over 25 per cent, due to the deepening recession and a
decline in interest rates. In contrast, Singapore regained its strength
towards the end of the year, as the appreciation of the Singapore dollar
helped soothe imported inflation.
South Korea's opening of its stock markets to foreign investment at the
beginning of this month is also worth noting. Up to Dollars 3bn of new money
is expected to flow into the market from foreign investments. Although
equity holdings by foreigners are limited to 10 per cent in a company, this
will provide underlying support for the market.
The economic environment, with high inflation and an increasing current
account deficit, remains unfavourable to the stock market. But with the
National Assembly and presidential elections anticipated, prospects for
increases in money supply providing economic stimulus ahead of the political
campaigns may be good news for equities.
</TEXT>
