<PROFILE>_AN-CAXBAADHFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920124
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Survey of FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (6): In a
good year the worst blows came from abroad
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AS THE UK stock market moved into the final trading quarter of 1991, fund
managers and analysts agreed that the best of the year was over, and that
there would be less to go for in the three months to December 31.
In broad terms, this view proved correct, though reality turned out to be
more painful than envisaged.
Few commentators had anticipated the degree of volatility which left the
market down by 4.9 per cent on the FT-SE index, the widely-used benchmark,
and yet more than 6 per cent above the low point for the quarter.
Few had predicted that the economic recession would prove as deep and
enduring as it has. Hardly anyone foresaw the rash of corporate setbacks
and, in the case of the Maxwell saga, the scandals that would fall on the
City before the end of the year.
The hardest blows for the UK market came from developments elsewhere in the
financial global community. The sudden fall on Wall Street and in Tokyo in
mid-November jolted London, as it did the other European markets. But London
held up relatively well, and confidence was not badly shaken.
More damaging to UK investment confidence has been the upward movement in
European interest rates, led by the Bundesbank just before Christmas when it
reacted vigorously to the challenge from France. The Bundesbank's move
effectively put an end to hopes of another early cut in UK base rates, which
had been sustaining UK equities.
Moreover, the blow to interest rate hopes brought domestic politics to the
front of the UK investment stage. Interest rate worries, spelled out by
rising house repossession rates, suddenly cast a cloud over the re-election
prospects of John Major's government, which must face the polls this year,
perhaps in May.
The Bundesbank's move put sterling on a razor's edge, where it has since
remained. The possibility that either UK interest rates might have to be
raised to protect the pound, or that sterling might be devalued within the
ERM, shook the stock market in December. The question remains on the table,
even though devaluation has been firmly rejected by the government.
If the fourth quarter had ended before Christmas, the Footsie, crushed by
this range of adverse factors, would have been more than 10 per cent off on
the period. But matters then took a surprising turn for the better as London
decided to put its faith in the authorities in the US and Japan, who had
reacted to recessionary pressures by cutting their respective interest rates
decisively.
The final week of the year saw the London market rise by nearly 150 points
on the Footsie, in response to Wall Street's sudden leap to successive peaks
on the Dow Average. But, with half the market on Christmas holiday, there
was little genuine institutional business to support the swing to
confidence.
The UK stock market had a good 1991, with the Footsie rising by just over 16
per cent and total return just exceeding that on government bonds. But as
the new year dawned, analysts sounded very cautious. Prospects for an early
end to the recession remain doubtful, and a question-mark hangs over
sterling. Add to this the possibility of a change of government, implying a
probable change of attitude towards privatisation and public financing, and
it is not hard to see why the analysts are cautious.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
